<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholars Issue Report on International Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars have aired
their views on security matters, mainly about China, in a report
on the international situation being published by the China
Society for Strategy and Management Research.
</P>
<P>
The report by the non-governmental research institute analyses
major security issues that occurred in different regions and
countries in 1997 and makes forecasts about possible changes in
the international security situation in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
The report focuses on ten items: the international security
environment for a growing China; the new US-Japan defense
cooperation guidelines and Sino-Japanese relations; factors
affecting long-term Sino-US relations; changes in the security
environment of Russia and Sino-Russian strategic partnership and
cooperation; security issues on the Korean peninsula; financial
crises in Southeast Asia and the economic security of China;
security dialogues between India and Pakistan; the United States'
involvement in Central Asia and the security of China; NATO's
eastward expansion and its strategic impact; and China's
diplomatic ties with the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The authors of the report are experts in international
relations at the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, China
Contemporary International Relations Research Institute, Beijing
University, and the China Society for Strategy and Management
Research.
</P>
<P>
The report is being published in both Chinese and English and
will be available after the Chinese Lunar New Year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
