<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Warplanes Strike South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli warplanes blasted a
number of villages in south Lebanon Friday afternoon after three
Israeli soldiers were wounded by Lebanese guerrilla attack, the
local radio Voice of the People reported.
</P>
<P>
The two successive air raids were carried out between the
villages of Aein Bouswor and Aein Gaonan in the Iqlim al-Touffah
area, just north of the Israeli occupation zone in south Lebanon,
the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Those targeted places were suspected by Israelis of the
strongholds of Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
However, the radio said that the raids did not cause any human
casualties, except that a villager's house was hit and destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The air raids came in response to the earlier attack by
guerrillas on an Israeli position at the village of Soujud inside
the occupation zone in which three Israeli soldiers were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Israeli army sources admitted the casualties, saying that one
guerrilla was killed in the attack, according to the radio.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 with an aim to protect its northern areas
from cross-border Lebanese guerrilla attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
