<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prospects Bleak for German Retail Business in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Wiesbaden-based Federal
Statistics Office today reported a fall of 1.5 percent in the
retail sales in the first 11 months of 1997, raising a gloomy
outlook for the German retail business this year.
</P>
<P>
The fall was far steeper than earlier expected, and was blamed
on continued weak domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
German retailers have also complained about unsatisfactory
turnover over the Christmas period. The statistics office expects
a drop of 1.7 to 1.8 percent in sales for the whole year of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the German retail association HDE reported that
Germany's retail sector had seen depression for the fifth
consecutive year in 1997, with turnover dropping to 714 billion
marks (397 billion U.S. dollars), 1 percent lower in nominal terms
and nearly 2 percent down in real terms.
</P>
<P>
It was also believed that the 1 percent increase in value-added
tax in 1998 would harm the retail business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
