<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Records Strong Industrial Output Growth in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. industrial output
grew steadily in December, helping 1997 that saw production rise 5
percent over 1996, the strongest in the last three years, the
Federal Reserve reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Production at the nation's factories, mines and utilities rose
a seasonally adjusted 0.5 percent last month as compared with a
robust 0.8 percent rise in November and 0.7 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
The 5 percent increase for the year compares with a 3.5 percent
gain in 1996 and was the best since a 5.4 percent increase in
1994.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the nation's industry operated at 83.4
percent of capacity in December, which was the highest rate since
September 1995 and up from 83.3 percent in November and 82.5
percent a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
At factories alone, the operating rate climbed from 81.5
percent at the end of 1996 to 82.5 percent a year later.
</P>
<P>
Some U.S. economists believe the strong investment uptrend of
recent years has enhanced the economy's ability to grow strongly
and provide new jobs without touching off increased inflation.
</P>
<P>
In December, the strongest production gains included advances
of 3.1 percent for semiconductors, 1.3 percent for metal products,
1.3 percent for clothing, 2.8 percent for tobacco, 4.2 percent for
coal mining and 1.7 percent at natural gas utilities. Auto, truck
and parts production sank 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Computer production rose 0.8 percent, which didn't match
previous months' rapid increases. Computer production at the end
of 1997 was 32.8 percent higher than the end of 1996. And
automotive production was 8.8 percent higher, even after the
December slump.
</P>
<P>
Other strong December-to-December production gains included
aircraft, 13.8 percent; semiconductors, 40.1 percent; industrial
equipment, 11.1 percent; iron and steel, 9.2 percent; and
electrical machinery, 19.5 percent. But leather products, down 9.5
percent December-to-December, and tobacco, down 1.1 percent, were
among the few sectors showing decline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
