<HEADLINE> Thailand Seeks Postponement of Military Debt Payment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai, who is also defense minister, Friday requested that the
United States extend the payment period of Thailand's debt owed
for the purchases of American arms and military equipment.
</P>
<P>
Chuan sought the extension during talks with visiting US
Defense Secretary William Cohen, who said on the occasion that he
understands the economic problems Thailand is facing and that the
U.S. will be cooperative with Thailand on the debt repayment
issue.
</P>
<P>
As for the eight F/A-18 Hornet jet fighters which Thailand has
ordered from the US, Chuan asked Cohen to consider three options
-- the order be canceled, the ordered aircraft resold, or the
payment period extended.
</P>
<P>
Cohen said the US will send a negotiating team in 10 days to
Thailand to discuss the matter in detail, according to Thai Deputy
Defense Minister Gen Vattanachai Wuthisiri, who was present at the
talks.
</P>
<P>
Thailand owes the United States hundreds of millions of US
dollars for the purchases of aircraft, frigates, tanks and
communications equipment.
</P>
<P>
On Friday evening, King Bhumibol Adulyadej granted an audience
with Cohen, who is on a 12-day Asian tour, which has already taken
him to Malaysia, Indonesia, and Singapore.  
</P>
</TEXT>
