<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Daimler-Benz to Re-Launch A-Class Cars on February 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Germany's Daimler-Benz AG said Friday
its car unit Mercedes-Benz will resume its delivery of its ill-fated
A-Class subcompact car on February 9 after improving its safety
standards.
</P>
<P>
The company made the remarks in an interview with German press
agency DPA.
</P>
<P>
The A-Class car, dubbed "Baby Benz", made its market debut last
autumn but was recalled later after several of them flipped over on
sharp turns during safety tests last October.
</P>
<P>
Mercedes-Benz has since refitting about 10,000 A-Class cars with
an electronic balancing system as well as lowered bodywork and wider
tyres.
</P>
<P>
The company said that the basic price for the improved version of
A-Class would remain unchanged at about 30,000 marks (some 16,500 U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In December, Mercedes said that it had 100,000 orders on its books
for the car, while 4,000 customers had cancelled their orders.
</P>
<P>
The Mercedes' factory at Rastatt near Stuttgart planned to start
out at 200 cars a day and raised the production to 800 daily as
quickly as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
