<HEADLINE> UK to Publish Name List of Wartime Assets Confiscated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government is to
publish a full name list of some 25,000 companies, partnerships
and individuals whose assets were confiscated by Britain during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
All these names to be unveiled were nationals of Germany or
countries allied with Germany in the war, but many of them were
victims of the Nazis, according to a report in today's Financial
Times.
</P>
<P>
Campaigners have been urging the British government to
compensate up to 25,000 victims of the Holocaust whose assets
worth some 600 million pounds (about 990 million U.S. dollars) had
been confiscated by Britain after the war.
</P>
<P>
Lord Haskel, a government official, said that the government
would also publish a detailed report outlining the history of
Britain's handling of property owned by nationals of enemy
countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1939 Trading with the Enemy Act, all assets invested
in Britain by enemy nationals, including victims of the Nazis,
were seized by the Custodian of Enemy Property.
</P>
<P>
Lord Janner, chairman of the British Holocaust Education Trust,
hailed the government announcement as a "landmark in the campaign
for justice and restitution for Holocaust victims."
</P>
<P>
"We want the names to be published very swiftly. The (British)
government should establish a procedure at once to enable any
victims, heirs or families who believe they lost money to make a
claim," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
