<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Bugging Law Approved by German Lower House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Germany's lower house of parliament,
the Bundestag, Friday approved a bill to allow German police to bug
criminal suspects in combating the country's rising crime.
</P>
<P>
The bill was worked out by the ruling party and the main opposition
Social Democrats (SPD) a week ago. Some deputies voted against it for
fear of police abuse. The opponents included the Greens Party and some
members of the Free Democratic Party, which is the smaller partner in
the Bonn ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
Prospects remains yet uncertain for the legislation which still
needs the approval by parliament's upper house, the Bundesrat, which
represents Germany's 16 federal states. The five states co-ruled by
SPD and the Greens are expected to either abstain or vote against it.
</P>
<P>
Under the legislation, which requires a change in the German
constitution, judges could approve police installing listening devices
in homes of suspects of serious crime, and of people who might carry
out major crimes, such as terrorism against the public.
</P>
<P>
However, police would be barred from bugging conversations between
criminal suspects and religious figures or their lawyers. The use of
information bugged from doctors and lawyers would also be limited.
</P>
<P>
The issue of police bugging had been debated in Germany for years
and such a need was made more acute only in the 1990s by increasing
organized and violent crime in the country.
</P>
<P>
Violent crime in Germany increased by 5.5 percent in 1996, showed
the latest available data. The number of crime cases involving the use
of firearms grew to 13,479 in 1996 from 12,855 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
German police launched 845 investigations into suspected organized
crime in 1996, compared to 787 in 1995. The economic losses organized
crime incurred were estimated around 2.7 billion marks (1.5 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
