<HEADLINE> EU Provides Payment Balance Aid to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission
announced today it was releasing 450 million Zimbabwean Dollars
(27 million U.S. Dollars) in crucial balance of payments support
to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
But the European Commission, the executive arm of the European
Union (EU), also gave stern warning that Zimbabwe's 1997/98
budget deficit should not exceed 8.2 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The money comes after intensive consultation between the
commission and Harare to help reinforce market confidence.
</P>
<P>
The EU said in a statement released by the EU office in
Harare, "the European Commission expects the government of
Zimbabwe to pursue its program of economic reform and fiscal
consolidation and strongly stresses that sound business
confidence and increased private investment are key elements for
sustained economic growth and poverty reduction."
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean cabinet a few weeks ago approved a document
detailing strategies of implementing a plan on the economic
structural adjustment program (ESAP) which ended in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe program for economic and social transformation
(Zimpest) set to rejuvenate the employment creation and
investment and it also has the task of fulfilling some targets
missed during the first phase of economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
Zimpest seeks to achieve an annual six percent GDP growth in
a drought year and a whooping 10 percent in a good year as well
as bring down the budget deficit to 6.5 percent of GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
