<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FSA Announces New Rules on Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Financial Services Authority
(FSA) announced today it has made rules extending cancellation
rights to investors buying shares in Open Ended Investment
Companies.
</P>
<P>
The FSA, launched last October by Chancellor Gordon Brown, has
the responsibility for regulating banks, insurance and other
financial organizations.
</P>
<P>
The new rules it announced today will allow more flexibility
for firms when providing "cooling off" for the sales of life
products and units in regulated collective investment schemes.
</P>
<P>
The new rules with effect from 1 March 1998 will allow firms to
introduce more cost effective ways of informing investors of their
right to cancel investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
They will be able to combine their descriptions of cooling off
arrangements with other information, for example, "reason why"
letters, contract notes, key features documents or marketing
documentation.
</P>
<P>
Firms will also be able to give investors a range of options as
to how they exercise their right to cancel.
</P>
<P>
While allowing firms to exercise more discretion as to how and
in what form they disclose cancellation rights to investors, the
FSA's priority has been to make sure the rules offer the same
level of investor protection as before.
</P>
<P>
Firms will, therefore, be required to comply with certain
investor protection standards when describing cooling off rights
to customers.
</P>
<P>
All the descriptions have to meet four key criteria on clarity,
prominence, timeliness and comprehensiveness, the FSA said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
