<HEADLINE> Clashes Leave Dozens Dead in Southeastern S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of corpses are now
littering on strategic highways in the interior, particularly in
the southeast of the country, commuters arriving in the capital
early today told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"We are alarmed over this development," said one trader from
Bo, in the south.
</P>
<P>
Military authorities said the corpses were mainly those of
civilian passengers whose vehicles have been either ambushed by
Kamajor militiamen active in the southeast under the code-name of
"Black December" or those of soldiers and Kamajors killed during
clashes.
</P>
<P>
According to one report, over 25 corpses were lying on the
Bo-Freetown Highway by Thursday morning, near burnt out vehicles.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Kamajors ambushed a civilian truck, killing six
passengers suspected to be soldiers wearing plain-clothes. They
were stripped naked and abandoned 10 miles to Bo, one driver
said.
</P>
<P>
Eight naked corpses were also abandoned five miles to Bo on
Tuesday. A military communique said the discovery was made by
soldiers on foot patrol.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, "identifications are out as some
of the corpses are badly decomposed and it is not certain whether
it is safe to stay longer in such areas which are prime targets.
</P>
<P>
Few vehicles are now plying roads in the southeast although
buses of the State-owned Road Transport corporation are making
the runs.
</P>
<P>
Heavily armed soldiers are making routine patrols along the
highway, particularly the Bo-Kenema road which leads to the
diamond mining areas of Tongo and the country's breadbasket
District of Kailahun.
</P>
<P>
According to the Military High Command in Kenema in the east,
the Kamajors "have resorted to hit and run tactics making it
difficult for the army to engage them in direct righting."
</P>
<P>
The Kamajors are tribal hunters backing President T. Kabbah
who was ousted by the military regime now in power in Freetown.
They are fighting to restore the rule of Kabbah. 
</P>
</TEXT>
