<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Reveals Nuclear Industry Reprocessing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Greenpeace today released a
confidential report presenting the actual figures for spent fuel
and plutonium to be reprocessed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the document, a total of 14,126.55 kg of plutonium
will be reprocessed by Cogema (France), while 4,180.84 kg are
planned to be reprocessed by British Nuclear Fuels Limited at
Sellafield (UK) during the same period.
</P>
<P>
Out of the quota to be reprocessed at La Hague, 6,953.71 kg
will be from the French utility EdF (Electricit de France), while
7,172.84 kg will belong to Swiss, German, Belgian and Japanese
utilities, Greenpeace said.
</P>
<P>
By far the largest quantity of plutonium will come from German
reactors, with 4,256.01 kg reprocessed during the year, it added.
</P>
<P>
In the case of reprocessing at the French plant of La Hague,
Japanese utilities will have 1,306.95 kg of plutonium reprocessed
during this year, said Shaun Burnie of Greenpeace.
</P>
<P>
"This is despite the fact that there is no commercial demand
for plutonium in Japan at this time," added Burnie.
</P>
<P>
As little as five to seven kg of plutonium would be enough to
produce one nuclear weapon, Greenpeace believes the report will
allow those opposed to reprocessing to have a better insight into
the operations of the secretive plutonium industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Trying to Rejuvenate Sugar Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique is aiming at an
annual production of 45,000 tons of sugar this year after its
sugar output dropped from 29,000 tons to 25,000 tons last year.
</P>
<P>
Tiago Wandschneider, adviser for the Institute of National
Sugar Industry revealed that the heavy rain which flooded about
1,000 hectares of sugarcane farm last year was the reason for the
production decrease, reported Mozambican News Agency today.
</P>
<P>
Wandschneider said that the lack of a national policy for the
industry is another reason for the production drop.
</P>
<P>
The policy vacuum has enabled the country to import sugar from
abroad, thus squeezing out the national sugar plants from the
domestic market, he said.
</P>
<P>
The domestic sugar market is estimated at 100,000 to 120,000
tons a year.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to unfold a new policy to levy
extra taxes on imported sugar, setting their imported price at
about 385 U.S. Dollars a ton.
</P>
<P>
This will help the domestic sugar industry attract foreigners
to invest in the country's sugar industry.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's sugar production reached its peak in 1972 with an
annual output of 325,000 tons, with only 45,000 workers. But now
there are 130,000 workers in the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
