<HEADLINE> UN Calls to Achieve Peace Goal in S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. team ended three days
of talks with the military junta in Sierra Leone today calling on
all partners to the Conakry Peace plan including ECOWAS and OAU
"to redouble their efforts to achieve the goals" of the Accord.
</P>
<P>
The team's leader, Francis Okello said at the press
briefing, "we are now half way toward the six-month plan but
there is still a lot of work to be done."
</P>
<P>
"If we don't do that we will fall behind the deadline (April
22 ) that was specified in the Accord," he said.
</P>
<P>
Okello said, "there is too much suffering around, too much
fear. We need to give Sierra Leone a sense of direction to get
the constitutional order in place so that the era of peace can at
least dawn on Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. envoy described the three days of talks as "good,
useful, open and constructive."
</P>
<P>
"We did not come here to negotiate or give or compromise any
thing but to discuss within the framework of the Peace Plan," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Five Foreign Ministers of the Economic Community of the West
African States (ECOWAS) signed the Conakry peace accord with
the military Junta in Sierra Leone which toppled a civilian
regime led by President T. Kabbah in May last year.
</P>
<P>
The Conakry accord signed last October demanded that the junta
hand over its power to the ousted civilian government by April
this year for a final end of the crisis. 
</P>
