<HEADLINE> Kuwait Refutes Iraqi Allegations Over Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Friday categorically
rejected Iraqi statements over an Iraqi opposition leader's visit
to Kuwait, saying it is normal to receive religious scholars from
various Islamic countries during the holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
This stance came in response to an Iraqi Information Ministry
spokesman's claim that "the visit implies a plan of aggression on
Iraq."
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi opposition leader Muhammad Baker Al-Hakim arrived
here last Sunday and is still staying. He has been received by
Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, Crown Prince and
Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah and a
number of religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the statement, an authoritative source in Kuwaiti
Foreign Ministry declared through official Kuwait News Agency that
the visit of Al-Hakim to Kuwait comes in the framework of Ramadan
month reception of religious leaders from various countries.
</P>
<P>
The source, who declined to be identified, said Al-Hakim used
to visit Kuwait during the holy month of Ramadan to meet Muslims
in Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The source said that "categorically rejecting the Iraqi
statements, the demeaning way and intentions as well as the
insolence as to objective realities, Kuwait is aware that Iraq is
still determined to fabricate justifications for its aggression
and threats against Kuwait and its people."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Iraq have tense relations since the seven-month
occupation of Kuwait by Iraqi troops in 1990. Kuwait was liberated
by the allied forces in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
