<HEADLINE> EU to Extend Funding Program to Palestine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
expressed its preparedness to extend for another five years a
funding program to Palestine.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Marin, vice-president of the commission in charge of
external relations, told the press that the commission thought it
proper to extend the funding program.
</P>
<P>
"The extension can be justified politically," said Marin at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
The European Union turned out to be the largest donor toward
the Mid-East peace process ever since the peace accord was signed
in Washington in 1993, with an amount of 1.68 billion ECUs in the
1993-1997 period, accounting for 54 percent of the total outside
financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
The current aid program ends by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The commission vice-president said that it was just like a
company. The shareholders have their seats on the board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
The commission was of the opinion that its assistance has been
instrumental in keeping the peace process alive and has helped in
the establishment of a Palestinian institutional capacity that
allows the Palestinian authority to carry out its basic functions
in a satisfactory way.
</P>
<P>
And the funding program has guaranteed a complementary role for
the EU in the Mid-East peace process apart from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Yet despite the massive outside assistance, the Palestinian
per-capita gross national product has fallen by over 35 percent
over this period, unemployment more than doubled to over 42
percent from 20 percent and yearly trade losses amount to almost
300 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Though the commission intended to extend the funding program,
it also said that the extension can only be made on the basis of
analyses of the situation in Palestine and of risk assessment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
