<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Welcomes WTO Ruling on Hormone Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission today
hailed as a victory the World Trade Organization (WTO) ruling on
the European Union's hormone ban.
</P>
<P>
The WTO's Appellate Body ruled that the EU has the right to
establish on a scientific basis a level of consumer protection
which it considers appropriate and which is higher than the level
resulting from international health standards.
</P>
<P>
The Appellate Body also upheld the EU view that the ban is not
inconsistent with other EU policies.
</P>
<P>
It found that the EU prohibition has not resulted in
discrimination or a disguised restriction on international trade.
</P>
<P>
But it maintained that the hormone ban in the EU is not based
on a risk assessment because the scientific studies do not focus
specially on residues in meat of hormone-treated cattle.
</P>
<P>
The Appellate Body agreed with the EU that the assessment of
the risk to human health is not a quantitative scientific analysis
by empirical or experimental laboratory methods associated with
the physical sciences.
</P>
<P>
The commission said today that it will now examine carefully
together with the other EU institutions and member states how to
implement the EU's international obligations, in particular with
respect to a new risk assessment along the indications given by
the WTO Appellate Body.
</P>
<P>
The commission said that the Appellate Body ruling has made a
valuable contribution to the development of clearer rules for the
conduct of dispute settlement which should be pursued further at
the upcoming reviews of the relevant WTO agreements.
</P>
<P>
"Overall, the Appellate Body report is an important
contribution to clarifying the rights and obligations of members
and is likely to increase the confidence of members in the dispute
settlement system of the WTO," said the commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
