<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Presses Peace Plan for S. Leone to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations special envoy
to Sierra Leone, Francis Okello, today called on all parties of
the Sierra Leonean crisis to redouble efforts for a peaceful
resolution.
</P>
<P>
The deadline of April 22 to end the peace process in the
country might not be met if all the parties concerned with the
implementation of the Conakry peace plan do not redouble their
efforts, Okello said.
</P>
<P>
Okello made the remarks at a press conference in Freetown,
capital of Sierra Leone, at the end of the three-day visit by a
UN fact-finding team led by him.
</P>
<P>
According to a British Broadcasting Corporation report
monitored here, the envoy called on the partners of the peace
plan to get together and assist forcefully and drastically in the
implementation of the accord.
</P>
<P>
Under the peace plan signed in Conakry, Guinea last October,
the ruling military junta, which seized power in a coup last May,
will hand over power to ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah by
April 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
But the junta said later the plan had become unrealistic,
citing hurdles such as the disarmament of its armed forces, the
release of the former rebel leader Foday Sankoh and Nigeria's
dominance in the west African peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
However, Okello said: "I continue to hope that there is a
strong commitment on both sides that the accord should be
implemented within the framework that would be available to
restore peace to Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
That means the constitutional order should be actually brought
back in place and the legitimate government of President Kabbah
restored to power, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the main purpose of the visit to Sierra Leone, Okello said
the eight-member team had had three days of successful working
visit to assess the infrastructures in Sierra Leone for the
deployment of UN military observers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
