<HEADLINE> US Congress Delegation Visits Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Congressman John Porter
has expressed the view that Cyprus' European Union (EU)
accession process may help move negotiations for a political
settlement forward on the island.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a meeting with President Glafcos Clerides
Friday, Porter, who is heading a four-member delegation visiting
Cyprus, said Cyprus' EU prospect would help achieve the
reunification of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
However, he described as "very difficult" the situation after
the EU Luxembourg summit meeting in December. The meeting decided
to open accession talks with Cyprus in April and keep Turkey out.
</P>
<P>
Porter said he discussed the issue during a meeting with
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congressman said his country has placed the solution
of the Cyprus problem "at a very high priority".
</P>
<P>
"Congress will make it a very high priority doing whatever we
can to help provide the environment that can make for successful
negotiations," he added.
</P>
<P>
Porter pointed out that there are suspicions and mistrust
between the Greek and Turkish communities in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"What we think is to alleviate those suspicions and get people
understand that they are in a secure position and can work through
negotiations," the Congressman said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress delegation, part of the U.S. Commission
on Security and Cooperation in Europe, has already visited
Athens and will visit Ankara after it ends its trip to
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
landed troops and seized the northern third of the island in the
wake of a coup seeking union with Greece. 
