<HEADLINE> OPCW Starts 2nd Training Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
THE HAGUE, the Netherlands, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-nine
specialists from 37 countries today gathered at Ypenburg to attend
a training program of the Organization for the Prohibition of
Chemical Weapons (OPCW).
</P>
<P>
The training course, to conclude within six months, includes
extensive traveling to various institutions specializing in
chemical weapons as well as in chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
The OPCW expects to select from the trainees highly qualified
professionals from a broad range of member states to make them an
integral part of the organization's inspectorate.
</P>
<P>
It is the second such training course organized and conducted
by the OPCW. The first one organized last year resulted in the
recruitment of 122 inspectors and four inspection assistants.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,500 applications for the second training course
were received by the OPCW. The applicants included specialists in
chemical weapons and munitions, chemical production technology,
chemical production logistics, medicine and emergency aid.
</P>
<P>
The OPCW is expected to finally employ 211 inspectors. It now
has 134 inspectors in 22 countries. 
</P>
