<HEADLINE> Cyprus Prepares Proposal on Turkish-Cypriot Role in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government will
put forward a proposal on Turkish Cypriots' participation in
Cyprus' membership talks with the European Union (EU), due to
start in April, Foreign Minister Ioanuis Kasoulides said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here, Kasoulides said "there is
no chance that we shall ever accept to start accession talks
under the banner of two communities."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the EU itself also stresses that such a
procedure is legally unacceptable as the European body does not
negotiate with communities but with recognized states.
</P>
<P>
During his recent talks in Athens, Kasoulides said, the
parameters of how to achieve Turkish Cypriots' participation in
accession negotiations were set out. But he refrained from
revealing any details.
</P>
<P>
This, however, he said, should be done without contravening EU's
position that it will carry out negotiations with the
internationally recognized government of the Republic of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus submitted its application for EU full membership in
1990. The EU summit in Luxembourg last December decided to begin
accession negotiations with Cyprus in April.
</P>
<P>
But Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash reportedly refused to
recognize the membership application the Cypriot government has
submitted to the EU and also refused to participate in the
official delegation of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides also expressed welcome to recent statements by EU
Council President, British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook that a
solution to the Cyprus problem is not a condition for the
republic's accession to the EU.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been partitioned since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island following a
failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
