<HEADLINE> Annan Urges Croatia to Dedicate Itself to Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- It is for the people and
the Republic of Croatia to dedicate themselves to the permanent
reintegration and reconciliation of the whole population, UN
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said today.
</P>
<P>
In his message to the ceremony marking the end of the mandate
of the United Nations Transitional Administration for Eastern
Slavonia, Baranja and Western Sirmium (UNTAES), Annan said this
ceremony marks the return of the region to the sovereign control
of the government of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general said the return is only the beginning of
a greater, more important return: the return of civility,
democracy, and the respect for life and liberty in the region.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief stressed the reintegration and reconciliation of
the whole population will not be easy or immediate. It is fraught
with dangers and will always require the good will of those
affected. It is the central, deciding condition of a lasting
peace.
</P>
<P>
Annan noted it is for the people and the Republic of Croatia to
dedicate themselves to the permanent integration and
reconciliation of the whole people.
</P>
<P>
On November 12, 1995, following four years of hostilities and
suffering, the Basic Agreement on the Region of Eastern Slavonia,
Baranja and Western Sirmium was signed. In January 1996, the
UNTAES assumed the authority over the region.
</P>
<P>
The UNTAES ended its mandate on January 15, 1998 after having
accomplished its key objective of peacefully reintegrating the
region into Croatia within the prescribed time frame of two years.
</P>
<P>
From January 16, 1998, the UNTAES will be succeeded by a
supporting group of 180 civilian United Nations police monitors,
mandated for a single period of up to nine months. The group is to
continue monitoring the performance of the Croatian police in the
Danube region and the return of displaced persons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
