<HEADLINE> World Oil Demand Forecast to Fall Due to Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Total world oil demand this year
is forecast to fall significantly because of the recent Asian
economic and financial crisis, said local press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The reports were based on figures offered by the Pairs-based
International Energy Agency's monthly oil market report.
</P>
<P>
The agency, which monitors global oil trends on behalf of the
main Western industrialized countries, was quoted as having
lowered its forecast of total world oil demand this year to 75.34
million barrels a day, 280,000 barrels a day less over last
month's estimate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the agency cut its forecast for demand in Asia,
excluding Japan and China, by 230,000 barrels a day to 9.39
million.
</P>
<P>
It had earlier before expected world oil demand to grow by
about 2.5 percent this year to 76 million barrels a day after
nearly 3 percent growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the agency said in its latest report that this year's
global growth is now expected to be slower at 1.64 million barrels
a day or 2.2 percent because of Asia's financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
It added that the oil demand could be affected even more if
Asian economies deteriorate further or the impact of the Asian
crisis outside the region becomes significant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
