<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey's RP Leader Barred From Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Turkey's largest
political party and the former Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan is
barred from politics for five years under a Constitutional Court
rule Friday.
</P>
<P>
The court, the top justice in Turkey, declared the closure of
Erbakan's Welfare Party (RP) on charges of destroying the nation's
secularism.
</P>
<P>
The court's decision was made after a eight-month-long
controversial campaign against the pro-Islamic party.
</P>
<P>
The President of the Constitutional Court Ahmet Necdet Sezer
announced that the court members voted for the closure of the
party with nine votes for and two votes against.
</P>
<P>
Six other RP members were also deprived of their rights for
engaging in political activities for five years, according to the
decision.
</P>
<P>
Sezer said that the court shuts down the RP as it seriously
violated the constitutional principles of secularism, adding that
"It is unthinkable to have a democracy without political parties,
but it does not mean that no limits should be put on them."
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of the RP closure, a new pro-Islamic Virtue
Party was set up on December 17, 1997 by some people with close
ties to the RP.
</P>
<P>
The veteran politician Erbakan and five other RP deputies will
lose their seats in the parliament and immunity from prosecution.
</P>
<P>
On the court decision for the RP closure, Erbakan, 71, said
that "such a decision is an incident of the grave law."
</P>
<P>
Turkey's True Path Party (DYP) Chairwoman Tansu Ciller, who
served as deputy premier during the joint government led by
Erbakan from June 1996 to June 1997, said the DYP is against the
RP closure.
</P>
<P>
The RP won 21.32 percent of the vote in the general elections
in December 1995 with the basic support from villages and urban
slums.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan resigned as prime minister last June under pressure
from the pro-secular military and other Western-style leaders who
criticized him for his reluctance to take tough measures against
fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan was borne in Sinop, northern Turkey, and he started his
political career in 1967 and later became the chairman of the
National Order Party. After this party was banned by the
Constitutional Court, Erbakan went abroad and stayed out of
politics for a while.
</P>
<P>
He returned to Turkey and continued his political career with
the National Salvation Party. This party was also closed with
other political parties during the military coup on September 12,
1980 and Erbakan was imprisoned in a military jail for a few years.
</P>
<P>
Following his release, Erbakan joined the RP, which was
founded on July 19, 1983, and became the leader of the party in
1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
