<HEADLINE> Greece Willing to Help Resolve Kosovo Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Greece today expressed its
willingness to help resolve the Kosovo problem which often leads
to violence due to renewed calls by the Albanian minority for
independence from Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at parliament today, Greek Alternative Foreign
Minister George Papandreou said that Athens would be willing to
host Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, Albanian Prime
Minister Fatos Nano and the leader of the ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo, Ibrahim Rugova, within the framework of any effort to
resolve the problem of large Albanian minority living in the
Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
As for Greece's position towards the Kosovo problem, he said
that Greece opposed Kosovo's independence from Yugoslavia and
respected the borders of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia,
coupled with prospects for wide-ranging autonomy for the province.
</P>
<P>
Albanians make up 90 percent of Kosovo's 1.9 million people and
violence there has been escalating recently following the
non-implementation of an education agreement reached between
Milosevic and Rugova.
</P>
<P>
In 1989, Milosevic revoked Kosovo's autonomy.
</P>
<P>
In November last year, Milosevic and Nano had for the first
time in 50 years discussed the Kosovo problem on the sidelines of
the first summit meeting of the Balkan leaders, which took place
on the Greek island of Crete.
</P>
<P>
No substantial progress had been made during their meeting, but
both sides agreed to continue their contact on the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
