<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Anti-Discrimination Committee to Hold Session </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The 18th session of the
Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women, the
only United Nations human rights treaty body that deals
exclusively with women's rights, will take place at the UN
Headquarters in New York from 19 January to 6 February.
</P>
<P>
During its forthcoming session, the committee will review the
reports of eight states parties to the Convention on the
Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women, which
was adopted by the General Assembly in 1979 and came into force in
1981.
</P>
<P>
The convention, which as of January 1998 had been ratified or
acceded to by 161 countries, requires states parties to eliminate
discrimination against women in the enjoyment of all civil,
political, economic and cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
Countries that have ratified or acceded to the convention are
legally bound to put its provisions into practice. They are also
committed to submit national reports, one year after becoming a
state party and then at least once every four years, on measures
they have taken to comply with their obligations.
</P>
<P>
In addition to reviewing reports and evaluating the progress
made, the committee will formulate general recommendation to the
state parties as a whole on eliminating discrimination against
women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
