<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes WTO's Report on EU Beef Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada welcomed Friday the
ruling by the World Trade Organization (WTO) that the European
Union's (EU) on imports of Canadian beef violates international
trade obligations.
</P>
<P>
Canada has not been able to export beef to the lucrative
European market since 1989, when the EU imposed a ban on beef
produced with growth hormones.
</P>
<P>
Canada requested a WTO dispute settlement panel in 1996 after
direct talks with the EU failed to resolve the dispute.
</P>
<P>
A WTO panel ruled in favor of Canada last summer. The EU
appealed, arguing that it has a right to set higher standards for
food safety.
</P>
<P>
Again, the WTO appeals body ruled that the EU didn't fully
justify the ban with its arguments.
</P>
<P>
"This is an important step forward toward resolving this
long-standing issue," said Canadian International Trade Minister
Sergio Marchi.
</P>
<P>
"I expect the EU to act quickly on the Appellate Body
findings," the minister was quoted as saying in a government
statement.
</P>
<P>
"We will pursue every avenue to have the EU market reopened to
Canadian beef," vowed Canada's minister of agriculture Lyle
Vanclief. 
</P>
