<HEADLINE> Zambia Works Out New Housing Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has worked out a new
housing initiative by setting up a revolving housing fund to
construct new houses and upgrade old ones, President Frederick
Chiluba announced here today.
</P>
<P>
He told the opening session of the parliament that new houses
to be built will be sold to public workers like soldiers, health
workers, teachers and other people who will not benefit from the
on-going sales of council and government houses.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will continue to implement its policy
to empower people to own houses, adding that the private sector
should take the lead in the provision of houses so that every
Zambian can have decent accommodations.
</P>
<P>
He said the scheme will also involve upgrading shoddy
townships that have mushroomed due to high urbanization.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba noted with sadness that while the government's
intentions to sell houses to sitting tenants is well meant, some
selfish individuals want to take advantage of the exercise and
amass wealth.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will open housing market to public and
private and make housing prices affordable for Zambians.
</P>
<P>
The council and government started to sell houses to sitting
tenants late 1996 as part of its new housing policy to support
home ownership. 
</P>
