<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Health Minister
Seyyed Mohammad Reza Khatami, brother of President Mohammad
Khatami, Friday criticized U.S. newspaper for distorting his
statement.
</P>
<P>
He denied the report that he has called for a response to the
president's overture towards the United States.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the Iranian official news agency IRNA, Reza
Khatami said a recent article in New York Times which quoted him
personally was "definitely a misconception and misapprehension of
the subject matter."
</P>
<P>
He said President Khatami in his interview with the Cable News
Network (CNN) last week had outright rejected any negotiation
between the governments of the Islamic Republic of Iran and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
In the interview broadcast on January 8, Khatami called for
dialog between the Iranian and American nations while stating
that Iran "feels no need to have ties with the U.S."
</P>
<P>
Khatami's remark was considered as a signal from the Iranian
government for resumption of relations severed in 1980 following
the occupation of the American embassy in Iran by Iranian students.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. Administration announced no change in its
policies towards Iran and conditioned any official dialog between
the two governments on an end to Iran's sponsorship of terrorism,
its pursuit of weapons of mass destruction and opposition to the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei today rejected
talks or ties with the U.S., saying that any talks or ties with
the U.S. would be harmful to the Iranian nation and the Islamic
system.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed the claim that Khatami's interview was an
indication of Iran's desire for rapprochement with the U.S.,
lashing out at the U.S. Administration and the American media for
making "hue and cry" over Khatami's interview.
</P>
<P>
Some observers here said that Khamenei's harsh remark was a
response to the repeated accusation of the U.S. government
against Iran.
</P>
<P>
Reza Khatami also said Friday that Washington's "repetition of
the empty claims against Tehran is a clear signal that the
U.S. is not willing to make any changes in its policies towards
Iran."
</P>
<P>
He termed the recent U.S. government's decision to study the
subject of sanctions on Iran, easing of visas for the citizens of
the two countries and the release of the frozen Iranian assets in
the U.S. as "minor steps in the direction of good intentions."
</P>
<P>
However, even if such measures were to materialize, they were
but minimal in nature for the removal of the bulky wall of
mistrust existing between the two nations, brother of the Iranian
President added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
