<P>
Early this month, Israel proposed that it will withdraw from
south Lebanon provided arrangements are agreed by Lebanon to
protect Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon rejected Israel's proposal, saying it is aimed at
separating the Lebanese track from the Syrian track in the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said he knew from
Lebanese sources that Lebanon is willing to accept the Israeli
offer if Syria allows it to do so, adding that Lebanon is in fact
a satellite of Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has 40,000-strong troops stationed in Lebanon, has
been enjoying special relations with Lebanon. The two countries
have vowed to conduct peace talks with Israel simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
During Hrawi's stay in Damascus, Assad will brief Hrawi on his
recent meeting with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak which was
held here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Assad and Mubarak discussed the latest developments in the
region and the upcoming separate talks between U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat next week.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon's internal affairs, especially the cooperation among
the country's troika, namely, Hrawi, House Speaker Nabih Berry
and Prime Minister Rafik Hariri, will be also on the agenda of the
talks between Hrawi and Assad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
