<HEADLINE> Greek Fishermen Continue Blockading Ports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Greek fishermen and sponge
divers today continued to blockade island and mainland ports in
protest against the new tax regulations.
</P>
<P>
Before the new tax regulations, Greek fishermen were exempt
from paying value-added tax (VAT) on their catch, but under new
tax regulations they would have to pay an estimated one to two
million drachmas (about 3,500 to 7,000 U.S. dollars) a year in
additional taxes.
</P>
<P>
Five days ago, the fishermen began blocking the ports of the
eastern Aegean islands of Leros, Patmos, Naxos, Kalymnos, Iraklion
and Santorini.
</P>
<P>
The blockades would be extended to the islands of Ikaria, Samos
and Fournoi as of today, a fishermen's union spokesman said.
</P>
