<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Govt Forgives Religious Leaders to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
has withdrawn cases which accused several religious leaders of
ridiculing other religions, in a move to avoid conflict between
different religions.
</P>
<P>
Inspector General of Police (IGP), Omari Mahita, said in a
statement issued in Dar es Salaam today that the government's
decision follows an appeal made by Christian and Moslem leaders
to Home Affairs Minister Ali Ameir Mohamed when they met on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Mahita said in the statement that the religious leaders who
have got involved in the cases include those who may soon appear
before the court and those who are still being investigated by
the police.
</P>
<P>
The religious leaders pleaded with the home affairs minister
for mercy at the Karimjee Hall in the city so as to open a new
chapter of co-operation between believers of the two different
creeds.
</P>
<P>
The government has announced that it will take stern measures
to punish people insulting religions of others, which is against
the constitution.
</P>
<P>
The minister said at the meeting that the government has
become fed up with irate preachers bent at sowing hatred among
the people in Tanzania, a country which enjoys prevailing peace
and tranquility.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting the religious leaders appealed to the
government to withdraw criminal cases facing some preachers, and
the minister promised to consider their request.
</P>
<P>
Mahita said he believes the government's decision to withdraw
the cases will act as a reminder for the preachers to refrain
from going too far.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that 32 percent of residents in Tanzania
are Christians or Catholics, 30 percent are Moslems, while the
rest holding indigenous beliefs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
