al-Sahhaf, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi stressed that
resolving the remaining disputes and differences between the two
neighbors would have positive effects on the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
He further underlined that the two countries would need to show
political will and national inclination to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf, who arrived here Friday night for an official visit,
also expressed the will and political willingness of Iraq to
resolve disputes with Iran.
</P>
<P>
"We seek to improve relations between the two Muslim countries
and we wish to overcome our differences through peaceful
negotiations and in a friendly environment," said the Iraqi
minister.
</P>
<P>
Close relations and cooperation between the two countries will
lead to the establishment of regional peace and stability, besides
securing their national interests, he added.
</P>
<P>
During their talks, the two ministers exchanged views on the
issue of prisoners of war, dating back to their brutal bloodshed
in 1980-88. Both agreed that the issue should be settled as soon
as possible.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that al-Sahhaf's visit here coincided with the
rising tensions between Iraq and the United Nations Special
Commission over arms inspection.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad improved relations with Tehran in 1990 before the
U.S.-led coalition forces drove its occupation troops out of
Kuwait in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahhaf was believed to have asked the Iranian government to
help in lifting the seven-year-old, crippling U.N. sanctions.
</P>
