<HEADLINE> S. Leone Announces Amnesty to Surrendered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A general amnesty for all
Kamajor militiamen who are willing to surrender to government
forces was declared in the southern Sierra Leonean city of Bo
Saturday, State Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Details of the amnesty were not made known but the radio said
the declaration was made by Captain Abubakarr Kamara, the
Secretary of State for the South, at a public meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to Kamara, "misinformation" has caused the strife
between Kamajors and government forces which led to a series of
violent clashes.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary of State presented a captured Kamajor, Sennesie
Koroma to the meeting, saying that all captured Kamajors "will be
humanely treated and would not come to any harm."
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said it is unlikely that the Kamajors will
accept the amnesty offer which comes at a time of intense buildup
by the militia group mainly in the southeast under the code name
"Operation Black December."
</P>
<P>
Army officials admitted to Xinhua that the Kamajors "pose a
threat to peace and stability in the Bo-Konoma District axis."
</P>
<P>
"If this is not quickly contained, the situation can evaporate
to other areas in the east including Kailahun where there is a
strong presence of former rebel combatants of the Revolutionary
United Front (RUF) now allied to the Sierra Leonean army," said a
military commander.
</P>
<P>
Casualty figures in various clashes are high and fightings
were sometimes brutal, according to human rights activists.
</P>
<P>
They recalled a recent incident near Zimmi in the south around
the border with Liberia where the heads of 16 soldiers cut off in
an ambush were paraded by dancing Kamajors.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing this to frighten our adversaries to make them
scared," one activist quoted a Kamajor leader as saying over the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Kajamars are traditional hunters backing former President T.
Kabbah who was ousted in a coup last May by the military junta
now in Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Military Commanders told Xinhua that they have "strictly
warned soldiers to deal with captured Kamajors as political
prisoners and not to ill treat them."
</P>
<P>
"We must not act as a warring faction but as a disciplined
force to defend the lives and property of all civilians," one
Commander said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
