<HEADLINE> HK Airport Operational Readiness Program in Full Swing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Airport Operational
Readiness (AOR) Program has moved into full gear following the
government's announcement that the new Hong Kong International
Airport at Chek Lap Kok will open on July 6.
</P>
<P>
The objective of the program is to provide a seamless
transition from construction to relocation and operation, said the
Airport Authority (AA), which oversees the program.
</P>
<P>
The program has been in place for many months to ensure that
all opening phase facilities are ready for operation, and that
some 45,000 personnel from the AA, 17 government departments and
more than 80 business partners are recruited and trained for their
duties.
</P>
<P>
The completion and commissioning of all opening phase
facilities, the mobilization and move to Chek Lap Kok and the
recruitment and training of staff are three broad areas of the AOR
program, each requiring a high degree of planning and
coordination.
</P>
<P>
A complex 90-day operation will take place for facilities and
staff to move from existing Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
The "Night Move" will be the most challenging phase of the
operation. During the move, staff and equipment essential to both
airports' operations will be relocated in the few hours between
the closure of the old facility and the opening of the new one.
</P>
<P>
All modes of transport will be used during the relocation,
including derrick lighters, barges and roll-on roll-off vessels,
and hundreds of trucks. Low-bed trailers and even aircraft will be
used to move extremely large vehicles and loads such as aircraft
engines, foam tenders, push-out tractors, loaders and passenger
steps.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
