<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe, France to Sign Trade Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe and France will sign
three agreements this year to improve bilateral trade and
investment.
</P>
<P>
French Ambassador to Zimbabwe Hadelin de La Tour-Du-Pin said
today that the two countries would soon sign a financial
protocol, under which over 240 million Zimbabwean Dollars (14
million U.S. Dollars) would be made available to the Zimbabwean
government to buy telecommunications and water supply equipment
from France.
</P>
<P>
"The two countries have already agreed on the protocol and
what is only left is the signing ceremony," he said, adding the
financial package would be part loan and part grant.
</P>
<P>
The second agreement, the ambassador said, would be an
investment and trade promotion accord which seeks to provide
security to investors from both countries.
</P>
<P>
"All the paper work has been done and we are hoping to sign
the agreement in the coming few weeks," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The third agreement, he said, would be for the establishment
of a French development fund to finance Zimbabwean rural water,
electricity and telecommunications projects.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe and France have already signed a double taxation
treaty to protect investors from both countries from being taxed
by both governments.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral trade is currently in favor of France with
exports of mainly telecommunications and electronic equipment
worth approximately 700 million Zimbabwean Dollars (40 million
U.S. Dollars) while Zimbabwe exported in 1996 mainly
horticultural and agricultural products worth 350 million
Zimbabwean Dollars (20 million U.S. Dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
