<HEADLINE> Major News Item in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Iran's spiritual leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, today
threw out water on the prospect of rapprochement between Iran
and the United States, which he described as "the enemy of the
Islamic Republic," and ruled out any contacts with Washington.
</P>
<P>
-- Stock prices around the world surged on Friday as
investors grew increasingly confident that Asian governments
will follow through on promises to strengthen their economies.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Scott Ritter, the American weapons inspector at the center
of the latest confrontation between Iraq and the United Nations,
left Baghdad on Thursday with his inspection team. The team's
departure added to uncertainty about what happens next.
</P>
<P>
-- Turkey's highest court placed an immediate ban on the
country's largest political party, finding it had a subversive
agenda and was working to replace the nation's secular order
with a rule based on Islam. 
</P>
