<HEADLINE> Rift Valley Fever Claims More Lives in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Amid the anarchy and
lawlessness in Somalia, the death toll by the Rift Valley Fever
is increasing as it is being seen in new places and towns around
the country.
</P>
<P>
The Southwestern region of Gedo records the highest number of
death due to the disease.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 people are reported to have died of the disease
in the town of Luq, about 350 km west of the capital Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to Ibrahim Mohamed Nur, the district commissioner of
Luq, the new fatalities have taken place in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Victims of the disease are mainly those who already lost their
properties during the recent floods that hit the region, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
"They lost everything from farms to livestock," said Nur,
adding, "the situation is critical."
</P>
<P>
Also in the central region of Galgudud, five to eight people
die daily of the Rift Valley Fever, said Yussuf Mohamed Eyow, one
of the elders of the region. In the districts of Adado, El-Bur,
Galhareri, Guri-El and Abudwaq, 80 percent of the fever victims
are children under five.
</P>
<P>
One of the chief elders of Galgudud region who contacted the
journalists via VHF radio here in Mogadishu said people don't
know what they're dying of.
</P>
<P>
"Some people complain about liver pain and vomiting, malaria
and diarrhoea or any other disease they heard before," said Ugas
Abdulkadir Ugas Hashi, "It is a mysterious sickness which has
never been seen in history."
</P>
<P>
In the capital where cholera is also persistent, the Rift
Valley Fever is killing people in a sporadic way in many parts of
the city. Three people die of the disease in Mogadishu daily.
Doctors in the capital say the Rift Valley disease is now
spreading much faster than malaria.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the Rift Valley Fever, the cholera epidemic is
still killing people in Mogadishu despite efforts by local health
authorities to cope with it.
</P>
<P>
The international aid agency of MSF-Spain and ACF-France have
provided large quantities of sodium solutions to fight
dehydration caused by the disease.
</P>
<P>
Each 500 ml. of sodium infusion which used to cost 15 U.S.
Dollars in the market is now sold a little more than three
Dollars, a relief for the cholera patients who could not make to
the four isolations camps which are operating with an overflowing
number of people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
