<HEADLINE> Normal Relations with India Hinge on Kashmir Issue: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif said on Saturday that only meaningful dialogues with
India over Kashmir can lead to normalization of relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan does not have any hesitation in talking with India on
other issues if the Kashmir issue is first solved amicably,"
Sharif told newsmen at the Lahore Airport after his arrival
Saturday afternoon from his three-day visit to Bangladesh. Lahore,
about 300 km east of here, is the provincial capital of Pakistan's
largest Punjab province.
</P>
<P>
"I am aware of the demands of the national interest," he said,
adding that the issue of Kashmir remains on the top agenda of the
working groups established by the two countries to normalize
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question about criticism by certain political
leaders regarding the government's overtures to India, Sharif said
the government was fully aware of the national interests and
realized its duties and obligations in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"As far as my nationalism is concerned the whole country knows
about my integrity and loyalty," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
