<BODY>
<HEADLINE> King Popov Upset in Swimming Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Four-time Olympic champion
Alexander Popov lost a gold medal to slow start at the world
swimming championships here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
William Pilczuk of the United States out-touched the defending
world champion to win the men's 50m freestyle sprint, producing
the biggest upset of the championships.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old American clocked 22.29 seconds for the title
while Popov, who had the slowest start of the eight finalists, got
the silver medal in 22.43.
</P>
<P>
Ricardo Busquets won the first medal for Puerto Rico as he tied
with Australian Michael Klim for the bronze. Both registered
22.47 seconds.
</P>
<P>
"I specialize in the 50 free. My goal here was to get second,"
Pilczuk said. "I thought Alexander was going to swim sub 22, that
was my prediction. So my aim was to beat Klim and Busquets.
</P>
<P>
"I had a good start and a great race at an opportune time. I
pride myself on my starts."
</P>
<P>
Popov blamed his loss to lack of concentration.
</P>
<P>
"I knew I lost the race from the block," he said. "I was too
slow. I was thinking about something else - I can't remember
what, but I was concentrating on something else.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, The Russian super star didn't lose his sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
"I've had enough of racing for gold," Popov said. "Now it's
time to concentrate on racing for silver. It's not everyday you
can get a silver."
</P>
<P>
Busquets was surprised with his own swim.
</P>
<P>
"Puerto Rico won a medal at the Pan Pacifics (last year), but
I'm not aware that we have won a medal at the world
championships," he said.
</P>
<P>
France ended its gold drought on Friday as Roxana Maracineanu
snatched the women's 200m backstroke final.
</P>
<P>
She clocked 2:11.26, beating German Dagmar Hase and Mai
Nakamura into the second and third places.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Brooke Bennett triumphed in the women's 800m
freestyle final, clocking 8:28.71.
</P>
<P>
Her fellow American Diana Munz got the silver with the bronze
going to Kirsten Vlieghuis of the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
World top-ranked Marcel Wouda won the Netherlands' first gold
here when he took the men's 200m individual medley in 2:01.18.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Xavier Marchand took the silver medal and American
Ron Karnaugh got the bronze.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 4x200m freestyle relay, Germany shook off a late
charge by the United States to clock a winning time of 8:01.46.
</P>
<P>
The American quartet finished second in 8:02.88 with the
Australians in third place.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Saturday, Russia's Irina Lashko and Vera Ilyina
finished 1-2 in the women's one-meter springboard diving final,
with Chinese Zhang Jing getting the bronze medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
