<HEADLINE> Uganda States Its Stance on Sanctions on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Uganda does not differ from
Rwanda on sanctions against Burundi, a spokesman of the Ugandan
president's spokesman said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni's position ''has been
consistent'' and it is aimed at bringing back Burundi and its
people into the democratic process and stopping the conflict in
the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman denied there is a rift on this matter between
governments of Uganda and Rwanda, saying, ''I am not aware of the
disagreement with the Rwandan government.''
</P>
<P>
He was referring to an earlier Reuter report which claimed
that there is a rift between Rwanda and Uganda on the sanctions
against Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an unnamed African diplomat as saying that
Uganda President Museveni wanted a tougher stance on the
sanctions forcing the Burundi authority to negotiate with Hutu
rebels in the country, but Paul Kagame, the Rwandan
vice-president, asked for a reprieve on the embargo during recent
visit by Museveni to his country.
</P>
<P>
The regional sanctions committee on Burundi is to meet in
Kampala soon to review the progress on implementation of the
embargo, said Steven Nabeta, the Permanent Secretary in Foreign
Ministry yesterday.
</P>
<P>
East and central African states backed by the Organization of
African Unity imposed sanctions in August 1996 on the Burundi
military regime which staged a coup on July 25 toppling the
civilian legitimate government in Bujumbura, forcingi it to start
talks with the Hutus in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
