<HEADLINE> Kenya to Allot Loans to Fight Water Hyacinth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government will
spend about 30 million Shillings (520,000 U.S. Dollars) on the
eradication of water hyacinth, the Daily Nation newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The money will be released in the next financial year starting
July 1, Natural Resources Minister Francis Lotodo was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Consultations were being held with the World Bank and other
experts on how to fight the weed and tenders for the procurement
of mechanical harvesters were opened last week, Lotodo said in
Kisumu Friday on a tour of the weed-infested Lake Victoria.
</P>
<P>
The procurement of the harvesters is part of the 77.6 million
Dollars the World Bank is to offer Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda
under the Lake Victoria Environment Management Program.
</P>
<P>
Kenya has so far got 32 million Shillings (554,600 US Dollars)
out of its 2.6 billion Shillings (45 million Dollars) share.
</P>
<P>
Sources said six firms have applied for the tenders, with
winners required to harvest 1,500 hectares of the weed at an
unspecified cost.
</P>
<P>
Officials in the Farm Engineering Industries of Kisumu said
the company is capable of harvesting a hectare of the weed in
three hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
