<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rains Cut Off Kenya's Major Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's a major road, the
Nairobi-Mombasa highway, was closed down on Friday night after a
30-kilometer stretch was cut off due to the raging floods caused
by the torrential El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
The road, serving thousands of commuters daily, is a life line
between Mombasa and sections of the hinterland in Kenya, Uganda,
northern Tanzania, Rwanda, Burundi and eastern Congo (K). Mombasa
is one of the busiest African ports bordering the Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The swollen Kambu River swept away a bridge near Kibwezi,
leaving no road link between the two largest cities in this east
African country until a new bridge is constructed, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Police spokesman Peter Kimanthi last night warned owners of
public and private vehicles against using the road until further
notice.
</P>
<P>
The police then had a hectic time controlling the heavy
traffic as vehicles coming from either Mombasa or Nairobi side
were turned back.
</P>
<P>
Two other bridges -- Athi River bridge connecting Kibwezi and
Kitui and Sofia Bridge linking Thika and Garissa -- were also
swept away during Thursday's downpour, said Kimanthi.
</P>
<P>
The only means of transport to Mombasa now is by air or train,
said the local press, adding that few people can afford the air
fares while transport by train is slow.
</P>
<P>
Heavy cargo from the Kilindini Harbor which is usually ferried
to the mainland in trucks will be badly affected following the
collapse of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
Hours before the road was cut off, the Kenya Association of
Manufacturers warned that the collapsing infrastructure was "a
danger to the country's economic development" and asked the
government to take emergency action to save the road.
</P>
<P>
Heavy downpours since Wednesday evening have flooded the
already collapsing roads in many parts of Nairobi and submerged
houses in some middle-class neighborhoods and shacks in teeming
shanty towns.
</P>
<P>
The rains have also added to a deteriorating sanitary
situation in the Kenyan capital, which was once rated one of
Africa's best-kept cities.
</P>
<P>
Nairobi was spared last November when the El Nino rains first
hit Kenya and wreaked havoc in Coast and North Eastern provinces.
</P>
<P>
President Daniel arap Moi said Thursday the government was
starting emergency food distribution to all areas under floods.
</P>
<P>
This year's long rains season, which should start from late
March in Kenya, may also be replaced by a spell of drought,
experts predicted earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
Global forecast indicated that the El Nino weather phenomenon
has been on a downward trend worldwide from December and was
likely to end in May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
