<HEADLINE> World's Largest Commercial Airship Built in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Johannesburg-based
Hamilton Airship Company will sell the world's largest commercial
airship to a South African company, local daily Saturday Star
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The sale of the airship will be secured within the next few
days. The buyer has expressed an interest in buying at least two
others in the near future, the report quoted an unidentified
source as saying.
</P>
<P>
The engineering design of the 55,000 cubic meter airship is
now more than 80 percent completed, and assembly of the first
prototype is due to begin within the next few weeks, the source
said.
</P>
<P>
It was learned that with a length of 129 meters, the airship
will be twice the size of a Boeing 747 aircraft and will be
capable of lifting loads of up to 60 tons. It costs about 25
million U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Project engineers believe that the first airship, which has
already been named "Nelson", will finally put South African
technology and engineering on the map.
</P>
<P>
"I think this (airship) will have the same impact that the
Concord had for Britain," said Graham Dorrington, chief engineer
of Hamilton Airship Company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
