<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayors From Around World Meet In Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Winter in the northern part of
China can be a difficult season for most people, but the mayors of
some northern cities are meeting in Harbin, the capital of
China's northernmost province of Heilongjiang, to discuss how to
make their cities more appealing.
</P>
<P>
Mayors from the United States, Canada, Japan, Denmark, Finland,
and China are discussing ways to exploit their winter resources.
</P>
<P>
Shirley Rudolph Timm, vice-mayor of Canada's Winnipeg, said
that buses in her city have installed devices for the elderly and
children to help them avoid slipping. Emergency medical care is
also available round-the-clock, children can get computerized
teaching at home, and local newspapers encourage people to go
outside in winter, she said.
</P>
<P>
Harbin's Mayor Cao Guangliang says that the people of Harbin
are creative and can use ice and snow to produce a wonderland. In
winter, large chunks of ice are carved into human or animal
shapes, or in the shape of famous architectural structures and are
given color with modern sound and light technology. People can
easily ignore the chilly air by walking in this dreamlike world and
it keeps the winter season from being wearisome.
</P>
<P>
People can also be found swimming in a path of water cut from
the thick ice of the Songhua River, while others ride sledges, or
go skating on the ice. Youngsters can enjoy themselves in some
3,000 ice and snow sportgrounds.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985, the city has sponsored ice and snow festivals to
attract tourists and to increase economic and trade exchanges with
the outside world.
</P>
<P>
Rick Mystrom, the mayor of Anchorage in the American state of
Alaska, said that people in his city used to spend long and dull
winters, but in recent years, the local government and citizens
have been working to make the city bright at night.
</P>
<P>
Tourist projects with a distinct winter flavor have also been
introduced and entertainment facilities are being built to attract
tourists, he said.
</P>
<P>
The idea about holding the conference among mayors of the
world's northern cities was first suggested by the mayor of
Sapporo in Japan in 1982. Up to now, such conferences have been
held eight times.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
