<HEADLINE> HK's Disaster Relief Fund's Grants for Quake Victims in N. China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's Disaster Relief
Fund Advisory Committee has approved here on Saturday grants
totaling 6.1 million HK dollars (0.78 million US dollars) for
earthquake victims in Zhangjiakou area in Hebei Province, China.
</P>
<P>
The grants were approved to World Vision Hong Kong, Jian Hua
Foundation Ltd. and Oxfam Hong Kong, three locally-based
organizations, as contributions to their relief operations.
</P>
<P>
Together with an earlier grant of 6.24 million HK dollars (0.8
million US dollars) to Hong Kong Red Cross, the Advisory Committee
has so far approved 12.34 million HK dollars (1.58 million US
dollars) from the Disaster Relief Fund for various projects to
assist the victims of this earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The Advisory Committee said that it will process an application
for funds from UNICEF as quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
The Committee, chaired by Chief Secretary for Administration
Anson Chan, called on the public for generous response to the call
of donations to help the victims.
</P>
<P>
The magnitude 6.2 earthquake hit an area 220 kilometers
northwest of Beijing, the Chinese capital, on January 10, leaving
49 people dead, over 2,000 injured, and 136,000 houses damaged.
</P>
