<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Design for HK Government Complex to Be Chosen Through Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
announced Saturday that it has decided to choose the best design
for the proposed Government Secretariat to be built on the Tamar
basin reclamation site through open competition.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Pau Shiu-hung, director of the
Architectural Services of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing Saturday afternoon at the Government
Information Service Department, Pau introduced a model of the
proposed Government complex to reporters. The complex consists of
an attached building, two main towers and a square.
</P>
<P>
He said that the competition may be an international one but
the timetable and other details about the competition have not
been decided yet.
</P>
<P>
Secretary for Planning Bowen Leung said Friday that the Tamar
basin reclamation site will be withdrawn from the land sales
program and be earmarked for relocating the existing Government
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The site, located between the Prince of Wales Building and the
CITIC Tower, occupies an area of 2.56 hectares on the waterfront
of Victoria Harbor. About half of the site was scheduled for
auction in March 1998 under the 1997/1998 Land Sales Program.
</P>
<P>
Leung said that the Government Secretariat located in the
Central Government Offices at Lower Albert Road and Murray
Building at Garden Road has been experiencing a severe shortage
of space for some years.
</P>
<P>
The sites occupied by the existing Central Government Offices
and Murray Building have a total area of 2.43 hectares. They will
be considered for commercial use after the relocation of the
Government Secretariat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
