<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Official Says Austerity Measures Already </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Press Secretary
Hector Villanueva said here Saturday that the Ramos Administration
has already taken concrete cost-cutting measures to bolster the
country's capability to cope with the current financial crisis
sweeping the Asian region.
</P>
<P>
Villanueva was reacting to reports on various austerity
measures being proposed by some senators to ease the impact of the
currency crunch on the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that President Fidel Ramos has already issued strict
orders to all government offices to cut their expenditures by a
minimum of 25 percent as part of the austerity measures being
implemented by the executive branch.
</P>
<P>
Villanueva said the different departments and agencies have
been tasked to determined on their own how such cuts would be
made, "but the bottom line is that such cost-cutting measures
should result in budgetary savings of at least 25 percent."
</P>
<P>
He said that while the government is not imposing a total ban
on foreign travel by government officials depending on the need
for such travels, "all unnecessary trips will be discouraged."
</P>
<P>
Exempted from the travel restrictions are diplomatic missions
arranged by the Department of Foreign Affairs and those involving
the World Trade Organization, International Labor Organization and
the United Nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, all other travels that can be done away with will be
discouraged, Villanueva added.
</P>
<P>
He said the President himself has demonstrated the seriousness
of the government restrictions on foreign travels by canceling his
scheduled trip to Davos, Switzerland, late month to address the
World Economic Forum.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Saturday, the Presidential Office
said that the president instructed Villanueva to explain the
austerity measures adopted by the executive branch in the wake of
reports that some senators have called for the scrapping of
"junkets" of government officials.
</P>
<P>
The office Saturday also re-published a series of
belt-tightening measures announced by President Ramos in his
administrative order early this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
