<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intensify Bilateral Trade to Minimize Use of Dollars: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Malaysian Prime
Minster Mahathir Mohamad said here Saturday that Indonesia and his
country need to intensify their bilateral trade to minimize the
use of dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Because the quantity of dollars and other hard currencies is
limited, (our) bilateral trade must be increased," Mahathir told
newsmen after a one-hour meeting with President Soeharto at his
residence in Central Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir arrived here Saturday morning for a one-day visit to
discuss regional economic crisis with Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister also explained the results of the ASEAN
informal summit held in Kuala Lumpur last December where Soeharto
was absent due to heath reasons.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he is here to offer a solution to the ongoing
monetary crisis in Indonesia, he said the two countries should
stand together to increase their trade without using U.S. dollars
or other foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir did not make any comment on the just signed reform
package between Indonesia and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF). "Indonesia decided these things on its own," he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Indonesia will conduct a
wide-ranging economic and financial reform, including reviewing
the 1998/99 State Budget, curtailing government financial support
for the national car project and scrapping some agriculture
monopolies.
</P>
<P>
In October last year, IMF agreed to provide 23 billion U.S.
dollars loans to Indonesia. In exchange, Indonesia vowed to
dismantle trading monopoly, overhaul the financial sector and
scrap or suspend costly infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF was reportedly dissatisfied over the
Indonesia's reforms in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
In November last year, Malaysia agreed to provide a one billion
U.S. dollar loan to Indonesia to help the country resolve its
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir and Soeharto last met during the APEC (Asia-Pacific
Economic Cooperation) Economic Leaders Meeting in Vancouver,
Canada last November.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir is the second ASEAN leader to meet Soeharto this week.
On last Tuesday (Jan. 13), the one-day visit of Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong also came here for an one-day visit to
discuss the economic situation in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, like other ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian
Nations) countries, has badly hit by the monetary crisis since
July last year. Its currency, the rupiah has lost more than 200
percent of its value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Mahathir directly left the president's
residence for home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ski-jumper Goldberger Applies for Olympic Accreditation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Triple World Cup ski-jumping
champion Andreas Goldberger has applied for accreditation to
compete in the NAgano Winter Olympic Games, organisers said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese justice ministry has been studying documents on
the 24-year-old star, who was embroiled in a drug scandal, as
Japan usually prohibits anyone convicted of a drug offense from
entering the country.
</P>
<P>
"As a matter of routine, we will consult the justice ministry
early next week," said Haruo Umegaki, head of the accreditation
section at the Nagano Olympic Organising Committee (NAOC), 21 days
before the opening of the Games.
</P>
<P>
"We will see if it is okay or not for us to proceed with
issuing an Olympic identification card for Goldberger," Umegaki
said.
</P>
<P>
The Austrian Olympic committee submitted an application for
Goldberger's accreditation "only recently," the NAOC official said.
</P>
<P>
Applications for other Austrian Olympians have been filed
earlier, Umegaki said.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Kokichi Shimoinabe said on Friday, "We shall
actively promote the Olympic Games but they should proceed under
rules. We have to check any problem that contraves rules."
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Vienna, Goldberger was fined 180,000
schillings, (about 13,000 dollars) by a Vienna court for
"possession of modest quantities of drugs" in 1996. He was
arrested with cocaine in his possession in a Viennese nightclub.
</P>
<P>
The court did not rule on whether Goldberger had taken the
drugs. Vienna authorities have since opened a judicial enquiry
against Goldberger for giving false evidence, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
The management of a nightclub frequented by Goldberger said he
had taken cocaine on several occasions. Goldberger had said he
only took the drug once, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Goldberger attempted to compete for another country after he
fell out with the Austrian ski federation following his statement
on drug use.
</P>
<P>
But he rejoined the Austrian national team last month after a
seven-month suspension imposed by the federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
