<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peg System Helps Stabilize Vietnam's Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The expansion of the peg system
for the Vietnamese dong against U.S. dollar has helped stabilize
the country's domestic currency market, reported the "Vietnam
News" Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to a year-end report by the State Bank of Vietnam
(SBV), commercial banks were allowed to widen the peg system from
plus or minus 10 percent of the official exchange rate last
October.
</P>
<P>
The report described the flexibility stemming from the widening
of the system as one of the bank's two major successes for 1997.
</P>
<P>
It had ensured no major fluctuations in the domestic currency
market, the report concludes.
</P>
<P>
The second success, says the report, is the bank's involvement
in settling Vietnam's commercial foreign debts through
negotiations with the London Club.
</P>
<P>
Also the bank listed its efforts in calling international
donors to grant Vietnam more official development assistance as
among its best performances for the year.
</P>
<P>
International and foreign donors have promised Vietnam about
2.4 billion U.S. dollars this year, almost the same amount as
provided the previous year, despite the regional economic crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
