<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading French Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers Saturday:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin presented Friday a plan to
develop multimedia in France. Schools, post offices and libraries
will be equipped with terminals of access, and the government offices
will be on the line in the next phase of development while
enterprises will be supported to innovate with multimedia. The
objective of the plan is to let France catch up in the field which
can create many jobs.
</P>
<P>
-- Accused of harming secularism of the state, the Islamic party
of Turkey, Refah, or Party of Prosperity, was dissolved on Friday by
the Turkish Constitutional Court, eight months after it was driven
out of power by the Turkish army. Its leader, 71-year-old Necmettin
Erbakan and five other parliament deputies were banned from
political activities, the properties of the party seized and its
local deputies and mayors became ``non-inscribed.''
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- A report by the Socialist government has expressed concern
over the balance sheet of treating the cases of juvenile delinquency
by some French institutions concerned, especially the most
complicated cases.
</P>
<P>
-- A nationwide demonstration will be held Saturday in France in
protest of unemployment. The anti-unemployment associations, the
trade union Confederation Generale du Travail (CGT), the Communist
Party and the Green Party have called on college students and clerks
to join them in the protest. 
</P>
