<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Threatens to Stop Cooperation with UN Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 17 (Xinhua)-- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
warned Saturday that the Iraqi government will stop cooperation
with U.N. inspection teams unless the U.N. remove the crippling
sanctions clamped on Iraq following its invasion of Kuwait in 1991.
</P>
<P>
In a nation-wide address marking the 7th anniversary of the
Gulf war on January 17, 1991, Saddam said Iraqi government has to
follow a recommendation by the National Assembly (parliament) and
is left with no other option to safeguard its interests and
expedite an end to the U.N. imposed embargo.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's National Assembly last December set a six-month
deadline for U.N. Arms inspection team to close the files of
weapons of mass destruction or risk an end to their inspection
tasks in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi threat came at a time when a inspection team of the
U.N. special commission (UNSCOM) left Baghdad Friday as Iraq
suspended cooperation with the team accusing its leader, an
American, of being a U.S. spy. But other UNSCOM teams in Iraq
continued their work.
</P>
<P>
Last October, Iraq and UNSCOM were on collision course after
Baghdad expelled American members of UNSCOM teams, who it alleged
were implementing Washington's hostile policy and prolonging the
sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The chief U.N. inspector Richard Butler responded by pulling
out all inspection teams from Iraq. The crisis was finally
defused by Russia who pledged to have Iraq's grievances
earnestly addressed by the U.N. Security Council and the U.N.
inspectors were allowed back into Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In his address, Saddam urged Washington to reconsider its
policy against Iraq so that there could be a quick end to the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"America should not be disillusioned to believe it can harm
Iraq. They (Americans) would retreat day by day from the peak
which they thought they had attained when they ventured (to hit)
the impregnable Baghdad with the bombs and missiles of
aggression," said Saddam.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Iraq's call for the revival of Arab
solidarity is not motivated by a feeling of weakness or by fear
and concern about the future of Iraq alone, adding that this call
has made a favorable echo among some Arabs who understand Iraq
and its leadership.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq's struggle against American global domination is
a struggle for the interests of humanity, world states, First
and foremost third world countries must unite against American
oppression.
</P>
<P>
"We hope and expect our friends in the world would understand
us so that each would assume a role emanating from its
responsibility, towards what is necessary to bridle the evil and
establish justice", he said.
</P>
<P>
The president described the U.S. as an arrogant, selfish
blind force that seeks to achieve its narrow interests at the
expense of other nations and societies and called it a
spiteful new imperialism despite all the trappings that are
intended to hide its real evil and ruthless nature.

 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0128 </DOCNO>
