<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Member States Divided Over ECB Executive Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, January 17 (Xinhua) -- With the Franco-Dutch row over
the presidency of the future European Central Bank (ECB) still not
resolved, a new row has developed only a few months ahead of the
decision as to which countries will be included in the first train
of the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The cause to the new row was the appointment of the six members
of the executive board of the ECB. The appointment was feared to
take into account the size of the EU member states and the
appointment mechanism has divided the members of the EU monetary
committee.
</P>
<P>
The matter will now have to be discussed, in a restricted
session, during the first council meeting of finance and economy
ministers of the EU.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is slated for next Monday in Brussels instead of in
London despite the fact that Britain is serving the six-month
rotating presidency of the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
The Treaty of Maastricht states that the executive board of the
future ECB will be composed of six members of one president, one
vice-president and four other members.
</P>
<P>
The first train of the Euro will theoretically carry 11 of the
15 EU member states after Britain, Denmark, Sweden and Greece
either opted out or were dropped out due to financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
The number of participating countries in the single currency
obviously exceeds the number of places on the ECB board.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht treaty also states that board members will have
to be chosen from "among persons of recognized standing and
professional experience in monetary or banking matters".
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources said that all the board members could come
in theory from a single member state.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, therefore, has proposed setting up a system of
predetermined rotation or enshrining a principle of geographical
distribution among the larger and smaller countries in designating
the board members.
</P>
<P>
Portugal, that wants to reserve three places on the board for
smaller countries, fears that the larger countries will
automatically take up all the places within the board.
</P>
<P>
Usually, Germany, France, Italy and Spain are considered,
financially and economically, the larger countries to participate
in the single currency mechanism to be inaugurated on January 1,
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
