<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 8:00 GMT, January 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- Kuwait has refuted a charge by the Iraqi
government alleging that Kuwait was acting to prolong
international sanctions against Iraq since its invasion of Kuwait
in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Trade Mohammed Mehdi Saleh recently accused
Kuwait of paying money for keeping the international curbs set by
the U.N. Security Council on his country. (Kuwait-Iraq)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
COLOMBO -- The Sri Lankan government is soon to carry out a
field survey, as part of a social security network program, to
look into problems that migrant woman workers are facing,
officials in the Presidential Secretariat said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They said currently there are at least 500,000 Sri Lankan women
 working in the Middle East while many others are employed in
other regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
The majority of those migrant women are married and mothers of
young children and their absence from their families has created
certain problems for those families, the officials said.(Sri
Lanka-Migrant Women-Survey)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi
Friday welcomed the initiative to call a meeting of the Group of
Seven (G-7) industrialized countries and those Asian countries in
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar, Supachai said the meeting is much needed
to tackle financial problems including strengthening the Japanese
yen and weakening the U.S. dollar to stimulate growth, the Bangkok
Post reported Saturday. (Thailand-G-7 Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey's True Path Party (DYP) Chairwoman Tansu
Ciller may stand trial in the Constitutional Court on charges of
misuse of office, semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The High Appeals Court upheld a ruling by a lower court on a
case involving Ciller, the former prime minister between 1993 and
1995, leading to a possible trial of her.
</P>
<P>
The lower court ruling said that a man had swindled Ciller out
of thousands of U.S. dollars by purporting to be a close friend of
her. And Ciller took the sum of money from a slush fund controlled
by her when she was the prime minister, the ruling
said.(Turkey-DYP Leader)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Anti-American sentiment is emerging in Thailand,
according to a Bangkok Post report Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Amnuay Yossuck, chairman of the Senate Finance, Banking and
Financial Institutions Committee, said his office has received
complaints from Thais who feel that the United States has taken
advantage of the economic turmoil to exploit
Thailand. (Thailand-U.S.)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
