<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria Rejects Lebanese Interference in Its </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Algerian Ambassador to Lebanon
Hasan Bou Fares has rejected a recent Lebanese government offer to
help end his country's cycle of violence, saying Lebanon has no
right to meddle in its affairs.
</P>
<P>
"We reject any attempt by Lebanon to interfere in our internal
affairs," Bou Fares said at a meeting with Secretary-general of
Lebanese Foreign Ministry Zafer Hasan on Friday, the local paper
Daily Star reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Bou Fares accused some "parties and committees, with nothing
in common except their criticism of Algeria, of holding meetings
under the cover of solidarity with the Algerian people."
</P>
<P>
"Had the aim of these meetings been to express solidarity with
the Algerians, there would have been a condemnation of the
terrorist group and actions being committed against the people,"
Bou Fares said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri urged at a
regular cabinet session that Arab countries should play an
effective role in helping end the Algerian massacres and said he
was holding contacts with some leaders to agree on the action,
which includes establishing a committee seeking to end the
violence in the country.
</P>
<P>
The next day, the offer prompted the Algerian government's
protest, saying Lebanon should not interfere in Algerian internal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
But the ambassador assured that he believed that Lebanon bore
no ill will towards his country and denied bilateral relations
were tense.
</P>
<P>
At least 75,000 have been killed in Algeria since an Islamic
insurgency erupted in 1992 when the government canceled
elections which the now-banned Islamic Salvation Front (FIS) was
set to win.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the Islamic holy month Ramadan, another
1,500 have been killed, according to press reports. The Algerian
government puts the figure at 254. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
