<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Closes Down 573 Newspapers, Periodicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China closed down 227
newspapers and 346 periodicals in 1997, a national press and
publications meeting revealed here today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting said that the move was to reduce the number of
poorly-run newspapers and periodicals, and only a few of them were
shut down because of violating government rules and policies.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also revealed that last year, China closed down
some 1,000 illegal book wholesale markets and confiscated dozens
of thousands of books containing pornographic, violent and other
illegal materials. The fight against pirated CDs and books was
also intensified.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, some high-quality newspapers and periodicals
had increasing subscribers. 1998's first issue of "Fortnightly
Chat", a political and news periodical edited by the Xinhua News
Agency, distributed 516 million copies, ranking first among the 21
periodicals with more than one million subscribers each.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government approved nine Chinese Communist Party
newspapers to increase their share on the market. Most Party
newspapers have achieved bigger distributions, with the sharpest
rise of 21 percent attained by the Shanghai-based "Wen Hui Bao".
</P>
<P>
The Press and publications Administration's principles in the
coming years are to further tighten management, adjust structure
and improve quality of the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
