<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Cold Wave Disturbs Normal Life in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Even Jaffir Hussain, the most
hard-working shopkeeper in his neighborhood, has been forced to be
a little lazy by a latest rare cold spell which gripped the
capital city last week.
</P>
<P>
It was already 10:30 a.m. when the 31-year-old man opened his
store Saturday in a small market in western Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
"I used to be an early bird and usually open my shop at 8:30
a.m. But it's unnecessary now. It's so cold that few people go
shopping in the morning," Jaffir said with a shrug of
helplessness.
</P>
<P>
Jaffir does have an excuse for his recent laziness. In
Islamabad, like in most parts of Pakistan which were hit by a cold
wave, business activities have been much affected.
</P>
<P>
As the mercury continued to plunge and icy wind turned biting,
people here became "hostages" in their houses. There was thin
attendance in bazaars and shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
The latest freezing spell followed massive rains and snowfall
last week in most parts of Punjab, Balochistan and North West
Frontier provinces.
</P>
<P>
The minimum temperature recorded in Astore Valley in the
Northern Areas was minus 13 centigrade. Quetta, provincial capital
of Balochistan, was the second coldest place with temperature
dropping to eight degrees below the freezing point.
</P>
<P>
Normal life has almost been paralyzed by the inclement weather
especially in hilly areas. People just stayed indoor and turned on
the gas heater even before the sunset, leaving most of the streets
and markets deserted.
</P>
<P>
In some northern cities, the residents faced severe hardships
as water pipes in these cities burst due to low temperatures
brought by heavy snowfall.
</P>
<P>
Sometimes the extreme weather turned out to be fatal. On
Tuesday night, a Russian-made Afghan plane crashed due to poor
visibility near Quetta, killing about 60 people on board. Also,
several people died of gas suffocation when they went to sleep
without putting off the gas heater in their house.
</P>
<P>
The cold wave in Pakistan is expected to continue for at least
another day as mainly dry weather was forecast to continue during
the next 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
Meteorologists here believe that the cold wave will not subside
until a rainy system hits the upper parts of the country in a
couple of days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
