<HEADLINE> Rwandan Vice President to Visit Brussels Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Vice President and
Defense Minister Paul Kagame is scheduled to pay an official
visit to Brussels next week for talks with Belgian government
leaders and the European Union (EU) officials.
</P>
<P>
The visit, due to be started on January 21, marks a growing
cooperation between Kigali and the EU, Rwanda's biggest donor,
according to a news release sent to Xinhua here today by IRIN, a
United Nations humanitarian information unit.
</P>
<P>
Kagame, a key figure in the Rwandan government, had
successfully put an end to the Hutu-led genocide in the country
in 1994 by leading troops to fight back from the neighboring
Uganda and defeat the Hutu troops in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
The central African state of Rwanda was a former German colony
before 1899. In 1916, during the first World War, it was occupied
by Belgian forces, and from 1920 on had been administered by
Belgium under a League of Nations mandate and later as a U.N.
Trust Territory. It became independent on July 1 1962. 
</P>
</TEXT>
