<HEADLINE> Iraqi Foreign Minister in Tehran for Normalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Foreign Minister
Muhammad Saeed as-Sahaf arrived here Friday night for his
first official visit to discuss normalization of Tehran-Baghdad
ties, Tehran radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his arrival, Sahaf said that his trip to
Tehran was aimed at settling remaining issues and normalizing
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He termed the future of Iran-Iraq relations as positive,
saying that ample grounds exist between the two countries that
could turn bilateral ties into a good neighborly relations
based on reciprocal respect.
</P>
<P>
After the end of the eight-year bloody war in 1988, the two
neighbors have not been able to normalize their relations as
issues of prisoners of war (POW), 100 billion dollars of war
reparation demanded by Iran remained unsolved.
</P>
<P>
Foreign diplomats here believed that Sahaf would also try to
win Tehran's support for Baghdad to break out of the isolation by
the West.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi parliament speaker earlier forwarded a letter to
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami, asking Iran, the present OIC
chairman, to help lift the U.N. sanctions on Iraq imposed on it
because of its invasion of Kuwait in 1990. 
</P>
