<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 07:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Rejects Iraqi Charges of Prolonging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has refuted a
charge by the Iraqi government alleging that Kuwait was acting to
prolong international sanctions against Iraq since its invasion of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In a reaction to the Iraqi charge, a Kuwaiti Foreign Ministry
spokesman was quoted by Kuwait News Agency Friday as describing
Iraq as having adopted a pattern in making lies and camouflaging
realities.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Minister of Trade Mohammed Mehdi Saleh recently accused
Kuwait of paying money for keeping the international curbs set by
the U.N. Security Council on his country.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said "the latest of these lies were made public
by the Iraqi minister of trade holding Kuwait responsible for
the longtime extension of the blockade and charging that Kuwait
paid money via certain channels to influence the decision-makers
in the world and maintain the sanctions."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait was the victim of the Iraqi aggression and such lies
cannot justify that crime that was condemned by the world, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman again differentiated the Iraqi people from the
Iraqi regime, saying that "the Kuwaiti people understand hardships
of the Iraqi people under international sanctions."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has welcomed the U.N.-Iraqi oil-for-food agreement as a
temporary measure to secure the humanitarian needs of the Iraqi
people, he said.
</P>
<P>
"While Kuwait backs continuation of the process according to
this agreement, it supports the current intention in the United
Nations to increase revenue of these oil sales to alleviate
hardships of the brotherly Iraqi people," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman asserted that the Gulf state cannot influence
the decision-making of the great powers, namely the five
permanent members of the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council so far has held 37 regular sessions to
review the U.N. sanctions against Iraq, but decisions were made at
the end of each session to prolong the curbs on Iraq in
retaliation for its failure to comply with the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti official spokesman stressed that "the Iraqi regime
must abide by the Security Council resolutions and scrap the
policy of procrastination and dodging instead of holding the
others responsible for the Iraqi people."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait repeatedly urged Iraq to fully comply with all the
Security Council resolutions relevant to Iraqi aggression of
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait also reaffirmed its stand that it was not against Arab
reconciliation, but there should be a "distinction between Arab
reconciliation and reconciliation with the Iraqi regime" and "the
two can never meet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
