<HEADLINE> China To Set up Publishing, Newspaper Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China is to establish a number
of big newspaper and publishing groups by the year 2010, with some
of them being transnational corporations.
</P>
<P>
A national press and publications meeting revealed here today
that there will be five to ten of the new groups that can generate
an annual sale volume of about 10 billion yuan (1.2 billion US
dollars) for each, and 20 to 30 capable of selling one billion
yuan of books a year.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided that some powerful Party newspapers should
be merged and re-organized, and newspaper groups will be set up
with Party papers at the core.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, newspapers with annual income of more than 100 million
yuan for each will account for 10 percent of the national total,
and 80 percent of the income will come from advertising.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 2,000 newspapers and publishes 100,000
kinds of books a year. But the industry's efficiency is poor as a
result of the planned economy.
</P>
<P>
For many years, a large number of Chinese publishing houses
have published books according to government mandates and ignore
readers' interest.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve the sector, China has decided to gradually
separate publishing houses from administrative departments, and
introduce various ownership systems into the industry.
</P>
<P>
The meeting asked publishing houses to pay attention to market
needs and consider readers' opinions, and create a sound
operational mechanism that goes in line with the socialist market
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Persistent Rains Revive Crops in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Most crops in Zimbabwe which
had been severely affected by a long spell of dry weather, have
improved significantly since the arid period broke.
</P>
<P>
The crops are responding well to the rains which have fallen
almost daily in most parts of the country in the last two weeks,
The Herald daily reported today.
</P>
<P>
Water supplies improved and significant inflows into dams have
been reported in most areas. Most rivers are flowing again. The
wet weather conditions also helped to improve the veld and
pastures in both quality and quantity, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In a crop and livestock report, the fortnightly Magazine
AGRITEX said agricultural activities increased throughout the
country with some farmers replanting while others weeding, hoping
the rains would persist.
</P>
<P>
The rainy weather was caused by the southern limit of the
inter tropical convergence zone, which was sitting on the
northern part of the country.
</P>
<P>
This, coupled with a cloud system from the west, has
maintained the wet conditions over most part of the country. The
airflow is expected to remain moist mainly in the northeast but
is getting progressively drier elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
AGRITEX said most of the early planted maize crop which had
been affected by dry weather was recovering following the current
rains. However, there are some areas where the maize crop is
suffering from moisture stress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
