<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
Crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week
mixed.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals market and the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM)
both closed the week lower while the Malaysian rubber market was
bullish.
</P>
<P>
CPO physicals started the week on a soft note which extended
until Wednesday, but rebounded on Thursday before closing the
lower on Friday.
</P>
<P>
January South closed the week 300 ringgit (71.4 U.S. dollars)
lower at 2,310 ringgit (550 U.S. dollars) per ton.
</P>
<P>
A supportive set of palm oil statistics was released by the
Palm Oil Registration and Licensing Authority (PORLA) for
December.
</P>
<P>
According to PORLA, Malaysia's total palm oil stocks for
December, 1997, was down 15 percent to 962,490 tons from 1.135
million tons in November, the total output of crude palm oil
declined 22 percent to 623,759 tons in December from 800,723 tons
in November, and palm oil exports for December stood at 644,258
tons against 640,418 tons in November.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals market is expected to perform better next
week in line with the rising trend in the ringgit which ended the
week at 4.1700 to the U.S. dollars on Friday from 4.5600 last
Friday.
</P>
<P>
On the KLTM, the week saw tin price fall significantly
following the recovery of the ringgit against the U.S. dollar and
the bearish undertone of the London Metal Exchange (LME).
</P>
<P>
After being depressed for four consecutive days this week, the
metal rebounded on Friday following strong buying interest and
ended the week at 21.52 ringgit (5.12 U.S. dollars) per kg, down
2.26 ringgit (54 U.S. cents) per kg from 23.78 ringgit (5.66 U.S.
dollars) per kg recorded last Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, accumulated turnover for the week rose to 539 tons
from 508 tons last week with European, local and Japanese buyers
dominating the bulk of the transactions.
</P>
<P>
The discount between the KLTM price and that of the LME
narrowed to 9 U.S. dollars per ton on Friday against 60 U.S.
dollars per ton last week.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian rubber market was however bullish this week with
February RSS One ending the week 15.5 sen higher at 300.00 sen
(71.4 U.S. cents) per kg and SMR 20 rising by 18 sen at 297.50 sen
(70.8 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
Technical adjustment as well as some buying interest especially
from Europe and the United States helped to push natural rubber
prices upwards this week, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
News that stocks of between 38,000 and 44,000 tons of rubber
stored in a warehouse in Hadyai, Thailand, were damaged when the
warehouse caught fire last week, also boosted market sentiment,
the dealer said.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization daily market
indicator price for January 15 was 201.07 Malaysia/Singapore cents
per kg against 192.36 cents on January 8. The five-day moving
average this week stood at 198.84 cents per kg against last week's
189.26 cents per kg.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
