<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Conduct Survey on Migrant Woman Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government is
soon to carry out a field survey, as part of a social security
network program, to look into problems that migrant woman workers
are facing, officials in the Presidential Secretariat said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They said currently there are at least 500,000 Sri Lankan women
working in the Middle East while many others are employed in other
regions of the world.
</P>
<P>
The majority of those migrant women are married and mothers of
young children and their absence from their families has created
certain problems for those families, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
The survey will be first conducted in Kurunegala, North-Western
Province, Matara, Southern Province and the capital city of
Colombo to identify the social and economic problems of the
families in respect of the basic needs of children, education and
health and nutrition.
</P>
<P>
Once the initial survey in the three areas is completed and
survey results analyzed, the project will be implemented
throughout the island country as a national program.
</P>
<P>
Presidential advisor Dr. Tara de Mel will supervise the
implementation of the program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
