<HEADLINE> 58,000 Postgraduates to Be Enrolled This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- China's higher education
institutions will enroll a total of 58,000 postgraduates this
year, with national entrance examination under way from January 16
to 18.
</P>
<P>
Enrolled postgraduate students will study at 415 universities
and colleges, 330 research institutes, and seven Communist Party
schools and military institutions, according to sources with the
State Education Commission.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the country, applicants for the exam totaled
274,000, an increase of 32,000 over 1997. Among the applicants,
161,000 are on the job.
</P>
<P>
Some 22,000 examinees aim to obtain MBA (master in busness
administration) diplomas, doubling the number in 1997, when a
unified national MBA examination was launched.
</P>
<P>
The number of education institutions offering MBA diplomas has
increased from 26 last year to 56 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filipino Official Urges Measures to Handle Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- One of President Fidel Ramos'
top economic advisers has called for effective confidence-building
measures to address serious economic problems in the Philippines,
a local newspaper said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Manila Chronicle, Socio-Economic Planning
Secretary Cielito Habito said the government "can no longer build
confidence by insisting that the country's fundamentals are good."
</P>
<P>
"Messages from the president and economic managers that the
economy is strong and that the country will easily weather the
regional crisis are no longer received positively," he said in a
memorandum to President Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Habito said that what is needed is effective confidence
building to counter the "negative psychology" that has been
driving market forces more than true market fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
The more the government insists that the fundamentals are
sound, he said, "the more it is inviting skepticism and losing
credibility."
</P>
<P>
Habito said the measures that the government has put in place,
or is proposing "are either not well understood, or deemed by many
to be not enough, not working, or outright wrong."
</P>
<P>
Sources in the Presidential Palace said the points taken up by
Habito were tackled at a meeting four days ago.
</P>
<P>
Since a Thai financial crisis spread to the Philippines and
other Southeast Asian countries last July, the country's currency
peso has fallen by 40 percent against the U.S. dollar, prices of
commodities have been increasing, and thousands of workers are
expected to lose their jobs in the course of economic adjustment
this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Diplomats Defend Position on Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 17 (Xinhua) -- European countries and the
European Commission joined hands Saturday in taking issue with The
Straits Times, one of Singapore's main newspapers, on the role
Europe plays in the world's effort to solve the current financial
crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
"Recent days' reporting and comments in The Straits Times have
given the impression that Europe is not fully involved in the
search for a solution to the financial turmoil currently affecting
Asia. This is not true," they said in a joint letter to the
newspaper, which published the letter on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The British High Commission, on behalf of the European Union
(EU) presidency, took the lead in signing up on the letter. The
others include ambassadors of France, Finland, Germany, Belgium,
Italy, Denmark, Austria, the Netherlands, Sweden and the
Delegation of the European Commission to Singapore.
</P>
<P>
They focused their criticism particularly on a Straits Times
report on Wednesday with the headline: Europe "cannot extend more
help to Asia" and charged that suggestions that Europe is taking a
back seat are clearly wide of the mark.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times used the headline when covering a lecture
delivered on Tuesday by Jacques Santer, president of the EU
executive arm, the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
"Europe's interests in Asia and its contribution to solving the
Asian countries' economic difficulties are far greater than you
imply," the letter argued, pointing out that EU exports to the
region in 1996 totaled 123 billion U.S. dollars, greater than
those from the United States.
</P>
<P>
In addition, since the EU governments hold 29.5 percent of the
IMF shares, the EU countries have contributed a significant
proportion of the resources made available by the fund and the
World Bank, the ambassadors said. They added that the EU countries
have also given strong support to the new IMF Supplemental Reserve
Facility while eight of the 13 bilateral contributions to South
Korea's second line of defense have come from EU countries.
</P>
<P>
In his separate letter to The Straits Times, Klauspeter
Schmallenbach, ambassador of the European Union and the Delegation
of the European Commission to Singapore, described the newspaper
headline as "absolutely misleading."
</P>
<P>
In reply, the editor of The Straits Times said Santer's lecture
was well reflected in the paper's report.
</P>
<P>
Santer "did indicate that 'we (EU countries) have to put our
own house in order in Europe. It is not easy', a point which
suggested that it was not in a position to extend more than
whatever was offered to the IMF," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
