<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Welcomes Calling of G-7, Asia Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Thai Deputy Prime Minister
Supachai Panitchpakdi Friday welcomed the initiative to call a
meeting of the Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized countries and
those Asian countries in financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar, Supachai said the meeting is much needed
to tackle financial problems including strengthening the Japanese
yen and weakening the U.S. dollar to stimulate growth, the Bangkok
Post reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said international cooperation is necessary to prevent an
economic collapse in Asia, which generates 60 percent of world
trade, and to save industries in the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the current Asian financial crisis would
affect global trade.
</P>
<P>
He said U.S. energy, aircraft and defense industries in
particular would not escape the impact of declining orders in
Asia, adding that there is also a large amount of European
investments in the region.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which holds the current presidency of G-7, on Thursday
affirmed support for the U.S. initiative for a top-level
international meeting on the crisis in Asia that would involve
leading industrialized countries and the affected Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
G-7 members are Britain, France, Germany, Japan, Canada, Italy
and the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
