<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-U.S. Sentiment Emerging in Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Anti-American sentiment is
emerging in Thailand, according to a Bangkok Post report Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Amnuay Yossuck, chairman of the Senate Finance, Banking and
Financial Institutions Committee, said his office has received
complaints from Thais who feel that the United States has taken
advantage of the economic turmoil to exploit Thailand.
</P>
<P>
He said an increasing number of Thai people are feeling that
the Americans are gaining benefit by forcing Thailand to open up
its market and that the United States is planning to take over
Thai companies at very low prices.
</P>
<P>
"We do not expect much from the U.S.," he added. "Even our
efforts to seek a review of the IMF (International Monetary Fund)
program may not succeed because we know the Americans will turn it
down."
</P>
<P>
He warned that the anti-American sentiment may spread to other
countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
During talks on Friday with Thai Senate Finance Committee
Chairman Suthee Singhasaneh, Suthee's visiting U.S. counterpart
and Republican Senator William Roth failed to make any positive
offer to help Thailand out of its economic crisis. He was just
concerned about how American interests would be affected in
Thailand and the region.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Thai Senate Speaker Meechai Ruchuphan said,
"You may now realize who our friends and foes are. So don't use
products made by the enemies and stick to those of our friends."
</P>
<P>
He said the current economic crisis should be a lesson for
Thais and they should remember "the bad things committed against
us by others."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
