<HEADLINE> U.S. Senator Opposes Deep Involvement in Thai Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 17 (Xinhua) -- William Roth, chairman of the
U.S. Senate Finance Committee, does not want Washington to become
deeply involved in the Thai economic crisis, according to a Thai
Senate committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
Suthee Singhasaneh, chairman of the Thai Senate Finance
Committee, held talks on Friday with Roth, who is on a visit to
Thailand to find out how the Thai economic crisis would affect
U.S. interests.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, Suthee said he believed that Roth, a
Republican senator, does not want Washington to get too involved
in Thailand's efforts to solve its problems to affect the U.S.
government's budget spending plans, the Bangkok Post reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Suthee quoted Roth as saying at the talks that American bankers
have remained on the sidelines since the collapse of Thailand's
finance sector because they are waiting for a clear picture of the
economy and want to see how Thailand would treat American
creditors of 56 Thai finance firms which had been shutdown.
</P>
<P>
After being briefed on the talks, Thai Senate Speaker Meechai
Ruchuphan urged his colleagues to avoid using products made by
"enemy countries."
</P>
<P>
When asked to name the "enemy countries" and comment on what is
seen as an emerging anti-U.S. sentiment in Thailand, Meechai
became evasive, saying he was not referring to the United States
specifically but to any countries which are "hostile" to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Since the monetary turmoil hit Thailand in mid-1997, the U.S.
government has not made any specific financial commitment to
helping Thailand's economic recovery, reportedly because of
disagreement between President Bill Clinton's Democrat
administration and Republican senators.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
