<HEADLINE> March Against Child Labor Starts in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A six-month global march against
child labor began in the Philippine capital of Manila Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ten thousand children and their supporters from trade unions,
church groups and non-governmental organizations are converging on
different points in Quezon City, Manila, to hold day-long
activities, including a march on Quezon City Memorial circle. The
activities will kick off the Global March Against Child Labor.
</P>
<P>
Their program includes singing, dancing and cultural
presentations and discussions on how to better improve the plight
of children. The activities will be capped by a candle light and
torch ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The global march, which aims to become the largest single
social movement in history in support of 250 million child
laborers worldwide, is a sea/land odyssey of children survivors
and advocates who will travel from country to country in an
attempt to push the child labor debates beyond national borders.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 major organizations worldwide agreed to have the
kick-off in Manila.
</P>
<P>
From Manila, the core marchers will be sailing to Vietnam,
Cambodia, Thailand and other countries in the region to continue
the march.
</P>
<P>
Such action will also be conducted in different European, Latin
American and African countries.
</P>
<P>
The activity will wind up in Geneva, Switzerland, in June when
delegates to the International Labor Organization convene to draft
policies to protect children against undue labor practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
