<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Loans Only Five Percent of Bank Credits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The proportion of bad loans in
China's banks is not as serious as many people believed, according
to Dai Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China (PBOC),
China's central bank.
</P>
<P>
Dai was quoted by today's China Daily as saying that if
measured with the internationally accepted gauge, bad loans
account for 5 to 6 percent of the banks credits, far smaller than
the 25 or even 40 percent some people anticipated.
</P>
<P>
As the country plans to write off this year 50 billion yuan (6
billion US dollars) of bad loans and more next year, the amount
will greatly drop, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
However, Dai stressed that although Chinese banks have no
danger in payment, they need to improve their management.
</P>
<P>
Dai said China has a different standard in grading credit
quality. All loans are divided into two categories: normal and
non-performed.
</P>
<P>
The latter category includes three parts: overdue loans, unpaid
for fewer than two years; idle loans, unpaid for two years or
more; and bad loans, which cannot be retrieved.
</P>
<P>
The genuine bad loans which need to be written off are only 5
to 6 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
Dai said the central bank will lead an overall clearance of the
bank loans and start to category them in accordance with
international practice. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
