<HEADLINE> Mongolia to Deepen Economic Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia will deepen
economic restructuring and consolidate macro-economic stability
this year so as to lay a solid foundation for steady growth.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the national newspaper Onoodor (Today),
Finance Minister Puntsag Tsagaan said that the government will
take a series of measures to achieve the above goals.
</P>
<P>
Specifically, the gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate will
be raised to 4.5 percent and the inflation rate be lowered to 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the exchange rate fluctuation will be contained
within five percent and the financial deficit be cut down to less
than eight percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Mongolia will further strengthen its
ties with foreign countries and international organizations,
particularly the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country will make special efforts to cooperate
with IMF for an early implementation of a medium-term economic
restructuring program.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Mongolia reversed economic declining and secured a
3.3 percent GDP growth. The inflation rate was lowered to 17.5
percent from 53.2 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
This macro-economic stability has created a condition for
attracting foreign investment to develop the mining and light
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
