<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Sea Lions Die of Hunger in Peru </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Fifty sea lions were found dead in
the last 72 hours along the beach in the Natural Reserve of San
Juan, near the port of Marcona, some 500 kilometers south of Lima.
</P>
<P>
Biologist Milena Arias Schreiber said thousands of sea lions
were starved to death recently in the Peruvian sea due to the El
Nino climate phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The dead sea lions are mainly puppies and females and the
survivers are hungry, the specialist said.
</P>
<P>
The warmer surface water caused by El Nino took away from their
habitat the fish they feed on, leaving the sea lions without food,
she said.
</P>
<P>
However, she dismissed the possibility that the sea lion could
be in danger of extinction because of El Nino.
</P>
<P>
El Nino phenomenon has occurred from time to time but the
species has survived, she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newspaper Sales Stabilized in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Newspaper circulation in Canada
appears to have stabilized after years of decline, reports said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
About 32.96 million copies were sold each week across Canada in
1997, just slightly below the 33.03 million sold in 1996,
according to the Canadian Newspapers Association.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent difference is within the range of reporting
errors, said the association, the main lobby group for Canada's
105 daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
Until 1997, newspaper circulation in Canada fell every year in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
"There may be a perception that circulation is falling, but
these numbers should put that notion to rest," the group noted.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Canada's weekend newspaper editions were up with
Saturday papers rising 0.3 percent and Sunday plus 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the weekday sales slipped by about 0.5
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
