<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johansson Officially Bids For FIFA Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Lennart Johansson, the UEFA
soccer president, was to officially announce his bid for the job
of the FIFA presidency at the preliminary draw of the UEFA
European Championships in Ghent, Belgium on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Highlighting his long opposition to Joap Havelange's 24-year
rule over the FIFA world soccer federation, Johansson said in his
election platform he will aim "to strengthen the democratic spirit
and establish a fair and accountable system" at FIFA.
</P>
<P>
The battle for the biggest job in the biggest sport seemed to
be a solo run as only the Swedish openly declared his candidacy,
although Havelange mentioned his sectretary general Sepp Blatter
of Switzerland would make an ideal candidate.
</P>
<P>
Johansson's support came even beyond Europe from the heads of
the Asian, African and Oceania federations and the International
Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
The FIFA President will be elected at a congress in the days
ahead of the June 10-July 12 World Cup in France.
</P>
<P>
Johansson said that as FIFA president, he would shed as much
power as possible to the continental confederations and limit
FIFA's presidential terms.
</P>
<P>
And he also opposes the landmark Bosman ruling which has
spawned professional free agency and a concentration of wealth and
talents within a handful of clubs and a few leagues.
</P>
<P>
"The Bosman ruling has been hurting soccer, endangering the
future," Johansson said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
