<HEADLINE> Four Rescued from Sinking Ship Off Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Four crewmen were rescued from a
sinking ship Friday in the Gulf of St. Lawrence, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen bodies were recovered by Canadian coast guard near the
180-meter-long sinking Flare, a Cypriot-registered freighter.
</P>
<P>
"Four are rescued," Canadian coast guard Lt.Cmdr. Glenn
Chamberlain was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They are hypothermic. Another's got a broken arm. But they are
at least on dry land and in medical care," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Five crew members were still missing and there was no more sign
of life, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The four survivors had been taken to hospital on the island of
St-Pierre, a French possession some 80 kilometers off the coast of
Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
The ship Flare seemed to have broken in half and slowly went
down stern-first in 40 meters of water off the French islands of
St-Pierre-Miquelon.
</P>
<P>
She was on its way to pick up grain from the Canadian city of
Montreal, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
