<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Creates Fund to Protect Stock Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange
(PSE) has set up a 200 million peso (5 million U.S. dollars) trade
and investor guarantee fund to cover for failed trade or delayed
payments for transactions between member brokers.
</P>
<P>
PSE President Jose Luis Yulo said here Friday that the PSE will
draw from the fund, which came from contributions by member
brokers and the PSE, to advance payments to clients whose brokers
fail to pay outstanding obligations.
</P>
<P>
It will also be used to cover for delayed payments for
transactions between brokers, he added.
</P>
<P>
"There is that fund so that all the investors are protected,"
the president said.
</P>
<P>
According to Yulo, the PSE will hold on to the membership seat
and other assets of any cash-short broker until the advances have
been paid to the PSE.
</P>
<P>
Local brokers are struggling to stave off the effects of low
value turnover and rising overhead costs by cutting operating
expenses, including salaries of employees.
</P>
<P>
Yulo expressed his confidence that despite the on-going
financial crisis, the small brokers in the country, which account
for 60 percent of the total membership of the PSE, would remain
financially secure.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine stock market should improve by the latter part
of this year, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
