<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructuring of China's Textile Industry Continues in 1998 (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 16 (Xinhua) -- This year will see
unprecedented and many painstaking reforms in China's textile
industry, when 4.8 million spindles are expected to be scrapped,
and 600,000 workers to lose their jobs as a result of cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
The industry expects to cut three billion yuan in losses.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 17.5 percent of the money-losing large and
medium-sized state-owned enterprises were in the textile sector,
involving 19.6 percent of the employees. In 1997, deficits at
state-owned textile enterprises were estimated at as much as 10
percent of all state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Shi Wanpeng, president of the China National Textile Council
(CNTC), says that problems in the textile sector are typical of
state-owned industries as a whole, so, improvements in this sector
may serve as a guide in reforms for the state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, the government plans to cut 10
million spindles and reemploy 1.2 million laid-off workers and
expects to eliminate all deficits in the textile industry.
</P>
<P>
Getting rid of spindles is the most difficult but the most
important part of the reform, Shi said, and the government is
determined to tackle the problem. The State Economic and Trade
Commission (SETC) will take charge of this in coordination with
CNTC, and local government will implement central government
policies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restructuring of China's Textile Industry Continues in 1998 (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Ma Yuliang, head of SETC's management department, says that
cutting the number of spindles does not mean selling them
elsewhere, as in the past, and there are administrative measures
to ensure the reduction.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhongyu, minister in charge of SETC, says that the central
and local governments will give three million yuan for every
10,000 spindles eliminated, and two million yuan in interest-free
loans will be provided.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government will also increase export rebates for
textile products, and allocate 15 percent of the quota of textile
agreements with North America and European countries directly to
textile enterprises that have a foreign trade license.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Wang said, production and procurement licenses
will be required for loom production and trade, and the government
will give export credit and 100 percent of export rebates for
looms.
</P>
<P>
Equally important, he said, are capital reorganization and
restructuring. Mergers, bankruptcies, personnel reductions, and
improved efficiency should be given priority.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the government will use most of
the 10-billion-yuan allocation to write off bad debts in the
industry, especially in large restructuring projects.
</P>
<P>
The re-employment of workers is being handled with great care,
Shi said, and basic allowances for them will be guaranteed. He
also spoke highly of the re-employment centers in Shanghai, which
play an active role in the effort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
