<HEADLINE> Colombian Coffee Exports to Fall in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Colombia, the world's
second largest coffee producer, will halve its exports of coffee
grains in February because of less harvest last year, authorities
said.
</P>
<P>
Colombia used to expert 400,000 bags (60-kilogram per bag) of
coffee grains in the month of February, but only 200,000 bags will
be available to the international market next month.
</P>
<P>
Caused by the El Nino climate phenomenon, coffee output in the
South American country dropped to 0.7 million bags last year from
11.9 million bags in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the past years, Colombia maintained a 14 percent share of
the international coffee market and the prices of its products
were the highest.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 6,000 Workers in Manila Laid Off in Last Two Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of workers in the
Philippine capital of Manila have been thrown out of their jobs as
the weakened peso forced hundreds of medium- and small-scale
industries to either close shop or cut down on production.
</P>
<P>
The Manila Times reported Saturday that in the last two weeks,
9,563 workers in Manila have either been dismissed or given
shorter working hours because of the country's economic meltdown.
</P>
<P>
Citing a report from the Department of Labor and Employment,
the paper said that during the period, 6,206 workers in the
capital lost their jobs outright, 1,440 were temporarily laid off
and 2,017 worked shorter hours.
</P>
<P>
The paper warned that more workers in Manila will be laid off
if the government fails to adopt measures to re-create jobs.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso has lost 40 percent of its value against
the dollar since last July and is now hovering around 42 pesos to
the greenback. The steep devaluation has brought about high
interest rates and made production more difficult in the country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said more than 10,000 workers in North Mindanao
will become unemployed in the next few months if the currency
crisis continues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
