<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Rally to Win Ice Dance Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Pasha Grishuk and Yevgeny
Platov rallied back to win the ice dancing title for their 21st
straight victory at the European Figure Skating Championships in
Milan on Friday.
</P>
<P>
From second place, the Russian duo scored four perfect 6.0s in
their free skate to Michael Nyman's "Memorial Requiem" to outpoint
fellow Russians Anjelika Krylova and Oleg Ovsyannikov.
</P>
<P>
"I'm so happy and relieved after yesterday's mistake there are
so much pressure," said the reigning Olympic and world champion
Platov who had a fall in the original dance.
</P>
<P>
With their difficult maneuvers and artistic touch, the Russian
pair, three-time European titlists, were surely hot favorite for
an unprecedented repeat of ice dancing Olympic gold medal next
month at Nagano.
</P>
<P>
Krylova and Ovsyannikov, second for the third straight time at
the Europeans, were innovative in their performance, but their
5.7s-5.9s were not enough to keep the lead they took Thursday.
</P>
<P>
France's Marina Anissina and Gwendal Peizerat took the bronze
medal.
</P>
<P>
In the women's short program, France's Surya Bonaly was second
to Szewczenko, followed by two-time defending titlist Irina
Slutskaya of Russia. The medals will be decided in Saturday's long
program.
</P>
<P>
Bonaly, European champion from 1991-95, showed she still can
skate at a high level despite a ruptured Achilles' tendon that
disrupted her career in 1996.
</P>
<P>
She rushed her return last year and was ninth at the
Europeans. She was not placed on the French team coming here until
two weeks ago, when Letitia Hubert withdrew with an injury.
</P>
<P>
In a jumbled set of scores, three-time world silver medalist
Bonaly was rated first by two judges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
