<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tent Lab Operational in Lop Nur for Sylvite Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese geologists have
established a tent lab in Lop Nur, a lake dried up in a desolate
area in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region where
China's largest sylvite reserve has been discovered.
</P>
<P>
Qi Jixiang, senior engineer of the Chinese Academy of
Geological Science is the only scientist working at the analytical
chemistry lab with only a floor space of as large as half of a
badminton course.
</P>
<P>
He said the lab is installed for future development of the 63
million tons of proved sylvite reserve in Lop Nur where China's
nuclear testing site was once located.
</P>
<P>
Qi said he once worked for more than 60 labs, including 8 field
labs, this one has the most simple facilities.
</P>
<P>
On the 6-square-meter "bench", which is made of piled wooden
boxes and test tubs, reagent bottles and scales and balances are
placed.
</P>
<P>
The sylvite exists in the underwater in Lop Nur and Qi's work
is to find out the age of the groundwater, water's flow rate and
directions. He said the data will be used for guidance of
development.
</P>
<P>
Since the Lop Nur lacks fresh water, Qi has to use little
amount of water to wash the tubs for several times.
</P>
<P>
He said: "though the condition of the lab is quite difficult,
the work is very competitive."
</P>
<P>
Sylvite is badly needed in China for making potash fertilizer,
which is of great importance for crop cultivation.
</P>
<P>
China needs three million tons of potash fertilizer annually
and now about 2.7 million tons are imported from other countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0207 </DOCNO>
