<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Non-Traditional Exports Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan non-traditional
exports amounted from January to November of 1997 to 4.335 billion
U.S. dollars, a 15.5 percent increase over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the amount, 3.162 billion dollars, or 72.9 percent were
exported by the private sector, and 27.1 percent or 1.173 billion
dollars by the public sector, the Central Statistics and
information Office has revealed.
</P>
<P>
Common metals was the product exported in the largest quantity,
with 39.1 percent, (1.699 billion dollars), followed by chemicals
with 15.55 percent (670 million dollars); materials for
transports, 8 percent (345 million dollars); foodstuffs, drinks,
and tobacco 7.1 percent (309 million dollars); and vegetable farm
produce 6.8 percent (296 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The United States is the main market for Venezuelan goods, with
1.108 billion dollars during the period.
</P>
<P>
Colombia bought 1.102 billion dollars, Japan 197 million
dollars, the Netherlands 174 million dollars, Mexico 170 million
dollars, and the United Kingdom 35 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
