<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 76-Year-Old Glenn Ready to Fly Back Into Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- NASA announced Friday that
the 76-year-old former U.S. astronaut John Glenn will be sent back
into space in October this year for research on aging.
</P>
<P>
Glenn, the first American to orbit the Earth in 1962, would
become the oldest man in space if his mission takes place.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Friday's press conference, NASA Administrator Dan
Goldin said Glenn is the right stuff as he has the unique blend of
"experience, expertise and excellent health."
</P>
<P>
Space is a good place for gerontological study because of
similarities between what happens to a body in zero gravity and
what happens naturally over time on Earth.
</P>
<P>
Glenn said he hopes medical experiments that will be performed
on him during flight will shed light on some of the diseases that
affect the 35 million Americans over age 65. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA to Investigae World Cup Ticket Sales on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The soccer's world governing body
FIFA said Friday it was investigating reports that tickets for the
World Cup finals were being sold at inflated prices on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
"We are taking these reports very seriously," said FIFA
general-secretary Sepp Blatter in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The London Independent newspaper said earlier that the French
Organising Committee (CFO) was looking at sales on the Internet by
a U.S. company, offering tickets far above their face value.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said FIFA had asked national soccer associations to
provide a list of the agents appointed to represent them for the
sale of tickets to their fans.
</P>
<P>
"Once we have these details, we shall publish them, in order
that fans will be able to know which outlets are official and
which are not," Blatter added.
</P>
<P>
Results of the investigation will not be available before next
week.
</P>
<P>
The organisers' move comes amid growing criticism from several
national football associations over ticket allocations for the
finals to be held in France from June 10 to July 12.
</P>
<P>
England, Belgium and the Netherlands have officially complained
to FIFA about their low allocations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
