<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Large Ship Sailing on Lancang-Mekong River on Dry Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese 300-dwt ship recently
successfully made its maiden voyage on the Lancang-Mekong River,
ending the history of large ships unable to sail in dry seasons on
the river.
</P>
<P>
It took 12 hours for the super shallow-draft vessel "Hongyun"
to make the 254 kilometer-long trip from Guanlei, a port in
China's Xishuangbanna, to a port in Thailand, via Laos and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The 4,880-kilometer river runs through China, Myanmar, Laos,
Thailand, Cambodia and Viet Nam.
</P>
<P>
Dry season arrives on the Lancang between January and April
when water level in some sections is as low as below two meters,
obstructing 100-dwt ships and larger ones. The sail of smaller
ships can hardly meet the growing cargo transport of China, Laos,
Myanmar, and Thailand along the river.
</P>
<P>
To cope with the situation, China has successfully developed
100-dwt, 200-dwt and 300-dwt super shallow draft vessels.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that by 2000, the annual passing capacity of the
river will be raised to over one million tons from the present
400,000 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
