<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 217 Families Missing in Snowstorms in Qinghai Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, January 17 (Xinhua) -- Two hundred and seventeen
families of herdsmen have been reported missing in the southern
part of Qinghai Province in northwest China, due to heavy
snowfalls there since last September.
</P>
<P>
The natural disasters have attacked Yushu and Guoluo, two
Tibetan Nationality autonomous prefectures in Qinghai, while
villagers in the neighboring Tibet Autonomous Region have been
combating the same kind of calamities in the same period.
</P>
<P>
The snowstorms, causing continuous low temperatures, as low as
minus 40 centigrade degrees sometimes, have brought huge losses to
local herdsmen in Qinghai's Yushu and Guoluo, two Tibetan
autonomous prefectures, next to the snowstorm-hit Nagqu Prefecture
in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, 117,200 heads of animals have been killed, and more
than 7,300 local herdsmen have been hurt or fell ill, due to the
snow and low temperatures.
</P>
<P>
Local experts attributed the heavy snowfalls to the unique
geographical conditions in these plateau prefectures, spotted with
mountains taller than 5,000 m, where warm fronts from the Bay of
Bengal and cold fronts from the Hymalayas meet. In the early 1996,
heavy snowstorms claimed 1.2 million livestocks.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government of Qinghai has paid great attention
to the situation by allocating five million yuan in relief funds
and sending work teams to the affected prefecturers, while the
provincial headquarters of People's Armed Police has also donated
relief goods worth 200,000 yuan to the victims.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,000 armed police soldiers have been dispatched to the
two prefectures, who have transported over 700 tons of relief
materials, rescued 274 local herdsmen, cleaned over 50 km of
snow-covered roads, removed over 20,000 animals to safe places,
donated 6,500 kg of food and 14,000 yuan worth of goods and
medicines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
