<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Former PM May Stand Trial for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's True Path Party (DYP)
Chairwoman Tansu Ciller may stand trial in the Constitutional
Court on charges of misuse of office, semi-official Anatolia News
Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The High Appeals Court upheld a ruling by a lower court on a
case involving Ciller, the former prime minister between 1993 and
1995, leading to a possible trial of her.
</P>
<P>
The lower court ruling said that a man had swindled Ciller out
of thousands of U.S. dollars by purporting to be a close friend of
her.
</P>
<P>
Ciller took the sum of money from a slush fund controlled by
her when she was the prime minister, the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
Under the parliamentary regulations, it requires just one tenth
of the 550 deputies' participation to introduce a parliamentary
investigation to the Ciller case.
</P>
<P>
If more than half of the deputies vote for the report, Ciller
will have to stand trial in the Constitutional Court.
</P>
<P>
Ciller had said in a letter to the lower court that she had
nothing to do with the case and demanded her name be deleted from
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference earlier Friday, Ciller said that
she and her party colleagues were afraid of nothing, adding that
such issues would only make the DYP stronger.
</P>
<P>
Some senior DYP leaders also accused the Higher Appeals Court
of taking a wrong attitude toward the issue, claiming that the
case was an ordinary one.
</P>
<P>
The Republic People's Party, one of the major parties in the
parliament, has announced that it supported a probe into the
case, demanding a lift of her parliamentary immunity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
