<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Supports Team Withdrawal from Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States on
Friday said it supported to withdraw an American-led U.N.
weapons inspection team after Iraq refused to allow it to
carry out its duty, but adding it was not a victory for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We support the decision to withdraw ... that particular
mission, in the face of Iraq's refusal to allow the team to do
its work," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday night, the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) in
charge of eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction decided
to withdraw the inspection team, led by American expert Scott
Ritters, on Friday, a day earlier than scheduled, after Iraq
blocked the team to discharge its duty.
</P>
<P>
Rubin denied that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein had won the
victory with the withdrawal of the Ritter-led team, saying it
was because "the international community was as united as it can
be in rejecting the premise that Saddam Hussein can deny a
particular group."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has accused Ritter of spying for the United States and
complained the unbalanced composition of his team with
substantial Americans and Britons in the team.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations on Wednesday unanimously adopted a statement
deploring Iraq's barring the inspection team from carrying out its
duty and required Iraq to allow U.N. weapons inspectors to do
their work unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
Richard Butler, U.N. inspection chief, will be in Baghdad next
Monday and Tuesday for talks with Iraqi officials on the banning
of the Ritter-led team and the right of his inspectors to have
access to all sites.
</P>
<P>
"Ambassador Butler was to go to Iraq and to try to convince
the Iraqis that if they don't change their ways and don't allow
Ambassador Butler and the U.N. to do its work, then there is no
way for them to get out of the sanctions hole they've dug for
themselves," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has stipulated that the sanctions imposed
on Iraq following the Gulf War would be lifted only after Iraq
fully complies with U.N. Security Resolutions to dismantle
weapons of mass destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
