<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Move Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 16 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks posted a broad
advance today, but with the Dow Jones industrial average rising
just 61.78 points to 7,753.55, a gain of 173.13 for the week.
</P>
<P>
The Dow rose more than 100 points twice during the session, but
pulled back at the end.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by more than a 2-to-1
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where NYSE volume totaled
665.84 million shares, much higher than 568.05 million in the
previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 10.78 to 961.51, and
the NYSE composite index rose 5.72 to 503.67.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 15.82 to 1,562.88, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index rose 8.45 to 663.99.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.50 to
426.25.
</P>
<P>
Stocks opened higher after the main index on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange surged more than 6 percent amid expectations the
government will take further steps to save Japan's troubled
economy. Other Asian markets also rose.
</P>
<P>
There was little market reaction to a Federal Reserve report
that the nation's industrial output grew solidly in December,
with the whole year production rising 5 percent over 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
