<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Waives Helms-Burton Provisions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today decided to suspend for an additional six months provisions
in the Helms-Burton law that would have allowed U.S. citizens to
sue third-country firms doing business in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"Today I am notifying the Congress of my decision to suspend
for an additional 6 months the right of U.S. nationals to file
suit against foreign firms trafficking in confiscated properties
in Cuba," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Last Summer Washington made a deal with the European Union,
waiving for six months the controversial provisions of the 1996
legislation, while the EU froze its own claim before the
Geneva-based World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The law, which was enacted early last year, was condemned
worldwide even by the allies of the United States including Canada
and EU countries, who prefer a different approach towards Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law penalizes third country companies doing
business in Cuba with assets that belonged to U.S. citizens or
corporations and were confiscated after the 1959 revolution.
</P>
<P>
Cuba and the United States have never settled the claims now
valued at more than six billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"In the past 18 months, we have worked with our allies and
friends to support concrete measures that promote peaceful
change in Cuba," said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the U.S.-led international approach" towards
Cuba must be "preserved, expanded and strengthened."
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, Vice President Sir Leon Brittan of the EU
Commission said that the EU and the U.S. will continue to
negotiate a settlement over their dispute over the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baltics, U.S. Sign Charter in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the three Baltic
nations today signed a partnership charter with the United States,
a step President Bill Clinton said could lead to membership of the
Baltics in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Presidents Lennart Meri of Estonia, Guntis Ulmanis of Latvia
and Algirdas Brazauskas of Lithuania joined Clinton at the White
House in signing the U.S.-Baltic Charter of Partnership.
</P>
<P>
The charter also includes a declaration of U.S. support for
eventual membership in the trans-Atlantic community.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Clinton said that NATO membership is
not guaranteed by the agreement. But he expressed hope that the
Baltics will in time walk through the door to NATO.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the America's security is tied to that of
Europe and Europe is "not fully secure" if the Baltics' security
is in doubt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lithuania Calls for More Trade with Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Lithuania intends to step up the
development of liberal trade with Russia, the Interfax reported
from Vilnius, the Lithuanian capital.
</P>
<P>
Gefiminas Miskinis, the Baltic state's deputy economic
minister, said that Lithuania had invited Russian government
delegation to Vilnius to discuss the bilateral trade and economic
cooperation between January 26 and 30, and continue the drafting
of documents aimed at creating a more favorable environment for
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Lithuanian side has suggested that the drafting document on
avoiding dual taxation be continued. The two sides have already
exchanged draft treaties on the protection and encouragement of
mutual investments.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the forthcoming meeting would focus on
reduction of customs duties and standardization and certification
of products to eliminate obstacles to trade between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Miskinis said that contacts between regions, cities, towns and
companies in Lithuania and Russia would promote trade and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized Russia was the main foreign trade partner for
Lithuania, but the potential of expanding mutually beneficial
relations had not been exhausted at all. "This is why Lithuanian
entrepreneurs want us to overcome problems faster and work out
treaties leading to more effective cooperation," the deputy
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The presidents of Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia, now in
Washington, are to sign with U.S. President Bill Clinton the
Partnership Charter on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Lithuanian side expressed hope on Thursday that Russia
would not reproach Lithuania with the signing of the U.S.- Baltic
Charter, which, it said, should not infringe upon the good
relations between Lithuania and Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
