<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baltics, U.S. Sign Charter in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the three Baltic
nations today signed a partnership charter with the United States,
a step President Bill Clinton said could lead to membership of the
Baltics in the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Presidents Lennart Meri of Estonia, Guntis Ulmanis of Latvia
and Algirdas Brazauskas of Lithuania joined Clinton at the White
House in signing the U.S.-Baltic Charter of Partnership.
</P>
<P>
The charter also includes a declaration of U.S. support for
eventual membership in the trans-Atlantic community.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Clinton said that NATO membership is
not guaranteed by the agreement. But he expressed hope that the
Baltics will in time walk through the door to NATO.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the America's security is tied to that of
Europe and Europe is "not fully secure" if the Baltics' security
is in doubt.
</P>
<P>
The document notes that the United States has a "real,
profound, and enduring" interest in their security and
independence of the three Baltic states.
</P>
<P>
The charter reaffirms U.S. policy that NATO's partners can
become members as each aspirant proves itself able and willing to
assume the responsibilities and obligations of membership.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and the Balitcs also establish a "Partnership
Commission" to review annually the activities of the bilateral
military and economic working groups.
</P>
<P>
"As part of a common vision..., the partners declare that their
shared goal is the full integration of Estonia, Latvia, and
Lithuania into European and transatlantic political, economic,
security and defense institutions," said the document.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference on Thursday, presidents of
the Baltics also said that the charter moves their countries
"closer to NATO" but is not targeted against Russia.
</P>
<P>
"It is not a substitute for NATO membership. On the contrary,
the charter is moving us closer to NATO," Estonia's Meri said.
</P>
<P>
"It clearly states the United States' policy agenda on the
strategic issues -- the security of the Baltic region and
Europeans a whole," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meri said the Baltic states' application to join NATO, which is
fiercely opposed by Moscow and has been shelved by the alliance
until an undetermined future date, was "the next big challenge to
NATO."
</P>
<P>
"Allies and partners, like NATO and Russia, do not need a band
of neutral states to stand in between them," Meri said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Documentary "A Voice of Her Own" Wins 1997 UNESCO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 16 (Xinhua) -- "A Voice of her Own ", a
television documentary about the impact women are having on
development as they take on new challenges and emerge from
traditional role, has won the 1997 United Nations Educational,
Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) Gold Medal, a
release from UNESCO said today.
</P>
<P>
Produced and directed by Andrea Kalin of Spark Media,
Washington, D.C., for the Asian Development Bank, the twenty-four
minute documentary focuses on intimate profiles in Cambodia, the
Philippines and Bangladesh as it tells the story of how the
economic empowerment of women can dramatically results in
transforming their societies.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 UNESCO Silver Medal was won by "Skin Deep: The Science
of Race" produced by the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation as part
of its The Nature of Things series.
</P>
<P>
The documentary explores humanity's penchant for sorting itself
into groups and seeks to break down the prejudices and myths that
have been associated with skin color.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Bronze Medal was won by Moise Shewa of Afro Wisdom
Films, London, for "Black Survivors of the Holocaust" which used
never-before seen archival film revealing the horrific treatment
of the Black and mixed race community in Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
The global UNESCO Awards competition was created in 1995 as
part of the celebration of the Organization's 50th anniversary.
The awards are intended to recognize worldwide television programs
that best exemplify the aims and ideas of UNESCO in addressing the
issues such as tolerance, human rights, democracy, literacy and
education, gender issues, social development, cultural diversity
and environmental preservation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980117.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-16 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Writethru: Turkish Pro-Islamic Party Shut Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's Constitutional Court
announced the closure of the pro-Islamic Welfare Party (RP)
Friday, dealing a heavy blow to the arising fundamentalism in the
secular republic.
</P>
<P>
Ahmet Necdet Sezer, president of the supreme judicial organ,
said there were nine votes for to two against towards the
shut-down of the country's largest political party, headed by
former Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
Sezer said that the RP was closed because of its clear
violation of the secular principles provided by the Constitution,
adding that democracy does not mean "no limits on political
parties".
</P>
<P>
As a result, Erbakan and six other senior RP members were
deprived of their parliamentarian status and barred from politics
for five years.
</P>
<P>
The case against the RP was filed with the Constitutional Court
by Turkish High Appeals Court Chief Prosecutor Vural Savas last
May on the grounds of the party's strong anti-secular stance.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the court judgement for the RP closure, Erbakan,
71, told a press conference that "such a decision is a judicial
mistake."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that it would be unconstitutional to shut down the
RP because a political party should not be held responsible for
the personal statements and behavior of some individuals.
</P>
<P>
The veteran politician had threatened time and again that he
would call for a judgement of the European Court of Human Rights
if his party was closed on the grounds of anti-secular charge.
</P>
<P>
The RP deputy chairman Ahmet Tekdal said no matter what
happens, the party will continue to advance its course.
</P>
<P>
Temel Karamollaoglu, deputy chairman of the RP parliamentary
group, had also said that those who made wrong judgement on the
case would be judged one day by history.
</P>
<P>
Tansu Ciller, chairwoman of the opposition True Path Party
(DYP), said that her party is totally against the court decision.
</P>
<P>
The DYP was a former partner of the RP-led coalition
government which governed the country for one year and was forced
to step down from the pressure of the powerful Turkish military.
</P>
<P>
The RP, founded on July 19, 1983, enjoyed wide support from
the poor, especially in rural areas and urban slums, as it often
provides economic aids to them.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to these voters, the RP won a sweeping victory in the
December 1995 general elections with 21.32 percent of the vote,
ranking the first in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, the RP's pro-Islamic tendency and its reluctance to
take tough measures against the fundamentalists annoyed the army
generals.
</P>
<P>
The powerful Turkish military, which regards itself as a
defender of Turkey's secularism founded by Mustafa Kemel, father
of modern Turkey, has repeatedly accused the RP of its support of
religious radicals.
</P>
<P>
It launched a nationwide campaign against the fundamentalism
since last year, also aiming to discredit RP's status.
</P>
<P>
While the RP-led coalition government was in power, the
Turkish military even sent tanks to Sincan, a city some 40
kilometers west of the capital Ankara, to show its determination
to defend Turkey's secularism. A pro-Islamic rally in Sincan last
February had caused grave concern among the military and other
secular forces.
</P>
<P>
The closure of the RP can by no means be seen as a last
victory of the secularists since its political followers might
emerge again under other names, observers said.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of the RP closure, a new pro-Islamic Virtue
Party was set up on December 17, 1997 by some politicians with
close ties to the RP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
